# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-broadcasting-corporation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The **Gulf War** was an armed conflict between Iraq and a 42-country coalition led by the United States.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The coalition's efforts were in two phases: **Operation Desert Shield**, which marked the military buildup from August 1990 to January 1991; and **Operation Desert Storm**, from the bombing campaign against Iraq on 17 January until the American-led liberation of Kuwait on 28 February.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 2 August 1990, Iraq, governed by Saddam Hussein, invaded neighboring Kuwait and occupied the country within two days.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The invasion was primarily over Kuwait's alleged slant drilling in Iraq's Rumaila oil field, and Iraq's large debt to Kuwait from the recently ended Iran–Iraq War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This led to Iraq annexing Kuwait's territories establishing Basra Governorate in the north and Kuwait Governorate in the south.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The invasion of Kuwait was met with immediate international condemnation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The UN Security Council demanded Iraq's immediate withdrawal and imposed a total embargo on products from Iraq and Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A coalition began a military buildup in the Persian Gulf region.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The broadest military alliance since World War II, its largest contributors were the US, Saudi Arabia, the United Kingdom, and Egypt.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Security Council issued an ultimatum to Iraq on 29 November 1990, expiring on 15 January 1991, to withdraw from Kuwait, with member-states thereafter empowered to use "all necessary means" to force withdrawal.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 17 January, the coalition began aerial and naval bombardment of Iraq and Kuwait, which continued for five weeks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq fired missiles at Israel and at Saudi Arabia, but failed to provoke the Israeli military response it hoped would split Muslim-majority countries from the coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 24 February 1991, the coalition launched a decisive ground assault liberating Kuwait and promptly advancing into Iraqi territory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The coalition halted its ground advance after one hundred hours, and declared a ceasefire.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In the war's aftermath, the Iraqi government suppressed a series of uprisings until 5 April 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Coalition countries responded by establishing two no-fly zones over Iraq's north and south.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The United Nations Special Commission sought to end Iraq's weapons of mass destruction programs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In 2003, another US-led coalition invaded and occupied Iraq, beginning the Iraq War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The conflict's environmental impact included Iraqi forces causing over six hundred oil well fires and the largest oil spill in history until that point.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] US bombing and demolition of Iraqi chemical weapons facilities were concluded to be the primary cause of Gulf War syndrome, experienced by over 40% of US veterans.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The conflict introduced live news broadcasts from the front lines of the battle, principally by American network CNN.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] It earned the nickname *Video Game War*, after the daily broadcast of images from cameras onboard American military aircraft.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Considered the "first space war", the US adopted satellite-based reconnaissance, communications, and GPS navigation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This was highlighted in the use of new military technologies including Precision-guided munitions and a stealth aircraft, the F-117 Nighthawk.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The largest tank battles in American military history were also fought, surpassed only by the Battle of the Bulge: the Battle of Medina Ridge, the Battle of Norfolk, and the Battle of 73 Easting.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The war was named *Umm al-Ma'arik* ("mother of all battles") by Iraqi officials.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After the US invasion of Iraq in 2003, the Gulf War of 1990–1991 is often known as the "**First Iraq War**".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Some authors have called it the *Second Gulf War* to distinguish it from the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] *Liberation of Kuwait* (Arabic: تحرير الكويت) (*taḥrīr al-kuwayt*) is the term used by Kuwait and most of the coalition's Arab states, including Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Egypt, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Terms in other languages include French: *la Guerre du Golfe* and *Guerre du Koweït* (*War of Kuwait*); German: *Golfkrieg* (*Gulf War*) and *Zweiter Golfkrieg* (*Second Gulf War*).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Most of the coalition states used various names for their operations and the war's operational phases.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Throughout the Cold War, Iraq had been an ally of the Soviet Union, and there was a history of friction between Iraq and the United States.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US was concerned with Iraq's position on Israeli–Palestinian politics.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US also disliked Iraqi support for Palestinian militant groups, which led to Iraq's inclusion on the developing US list of State Sponsors of Terrorism in December 1979.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US remained officially neutral after Iraq's invasion of Iran in 1980, which became the Iran–Iraq War, although it provided resources, political support, and some "non-military" aircraft to Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In March 1982, Iran began a successful counteroffensive (Operation Undeniable Victory), and the US increased its support for Iraq to prevent Iran from forcing a surrender.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In a US bid to open full diplomatic relations with Iraq, the country was removed from the US list of State Sponsors of Terrorism.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Ostensibly, this was because of improvement in the regime's record, although former US assistant defense secretary Noel Koch later stated: "No one had any doubts about [the Iraqis'] continued involvement in terrorism ...
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] With Iraq's newfound success in the war, and the Iranian rebuff of a peace offer in July, arms sales to Iraq reached a record spike in 1982.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] When Iraqi president Saddam Hussein expelled Abu Nidal to Syria at the US's request in November 1983, the Reagan administration sent Donald Rumsfeld to meet Saddam as a special envoy and to cultivate ties.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] By the time the ceasefire with Iran was signed in August 1988, Iraq was heavily debt-ridden and tensions within society were rising.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Most of its debt was owed to Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq's debts to Kuwait amounted to $14 billion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq pressured both nations to forgive the debts, but they refused.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraq–Kuwait border dispute involved Iraqi claims to Kuwaiti territory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Kuwait had been a part of the Ottoman Empire's province of Basra, something that Iraq claimed made Kuwait rightful Iraqi territory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Kuwait's ruling dynasty, the al-Sabah family, had concluded a protectorate agreement in 1899 that assigned responsibility for Kuwait's foreign affairs to the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The UK drew the border between Kuwait and Iraq in 1922, making Iraq almost entirely landlocked.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Kuwait rejected Iraqi attempts to secure further provisions in the region.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq also accused Kuwait of exceeding its OPEC quotas for oil production.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In order for the cartel to maintain its desired price of $18 per barrel, discipline was required.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The United Arab Emirates and Kuwait were consistently overproducing; the latter at least in part to repair losses caused by Iranian attacks in the Iran–Iraq War and to pay for the losses of an economic scandal.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The result was a slump in the oil price – as low as $10 per barrel ($63/m3) – with a resulting loss of $7 billion a year to Iraq, equal to its 1989 balance of payments deficit.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Resulting revenues struggled to support the government's basic costs, let alone repair Iraq's damaged infrastructure.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Jordan and Iraq both looked for more discipline, with little success.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraqi government described it as a form of economic warfare, which it claimed was aggravated by Kuwait slant-drilling across the border into Iraq's Rumaila oil field.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] According to oil workers in the area, Iraq's slant drilling claim was fabricated, as "oil flows easily from the Rumaila field without any need for these techniques." At the same time, Saddam looked for closer ties with those Arab states that had supported Iraq in the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This move was supported by the US, who believed that Iraqi ties with pro-Western Gulf states would help bring and maintain Iraq inside the US' sphere of influence.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In 1989, it appeared that Saudi–Iraqi relations, strong during the war, would be maintained.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A pact of non-interference and non-aggression was signed between the countries, followed by a Kuwaiti-Iraqi deal for Iraq to supply Kuwait with water for drinking and irrigation, although a request for Kuwait to lease Iraq Umm Qasr was rejected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Saudi-backed development projects were hampered by Iraq's large debts, even with the demobilization of 200,000 soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq also looked to increase arms production so as to become an exporter, although the success of these projects was also restrained by Iraq's obligations; in Iraq, resentment to OPEC's controls mounted.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq's relations with its Arab neighbors, particularly Egypt, were degraded by mounting violence in Iraq against expatriate groups, who were well-employed during the war, by unemployed Iraqis, among them demobilized soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] These events drew little notice outside the Arab world because of fast-moving events directly related to the fall of Communism in Eastern Europe.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] However, the US did begin to condemn Iraq's human rights record, including the well-known use of torture.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The UK also condemned the execution of Farzad Bazoft, a journalist working for the British newspaper *The Observer*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Following Saddam's declaration that "binary chemical weapons" would be used on Israel if it used military force against Iraq, Washington halted part of its funding.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A UN mission to the Israeli-occupied territories, where riots had resulted in Palestinian deaths, was vetoed by the US, making Iraq deeply skeptical of US foreign policy aims in the region, combined with the reliance of the US on Middle Eastern energy reserves.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In early July 1990, Iraq complained about Kuwait's behavior, such as not respecting their quota, and openly threatened to take military action.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On the 23rd, the CIA reported that Iraq had moved 30,000 troops to the Iraq–Kuwait border, and the US naval fleet in the Persian Gulf was placed on alert.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Saddam believed an anti-Iraq conspiracy was developing – Kuwait had begun talks with Iran, and Iraq's rival Syria had arranged a visit to Egypt.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] He threatened force against Kuwait and the UAE, saying: "The policies of some Arab rulers are American ...
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] They are inspired by America to undermine Arab interests and security." The US sent aerial refuelling planes and combat ships to the Persian Gulf in response to these threats.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Discussions in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, mediated on the Arab League's behalf by Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak, were held on 31 July and led Mubarak to believe that a peaceful course could be established.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On the 25th, Saddam met with April Glaspie, the US ambassador to Iraq, in Baghdad.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] According to Glaspie's own account, she stated in reference to the precise border between Kuwait and Iraq, "... that she had served in Kuwait 20 years before; 'then, as now, we took no position on these Arab affairs'." Glaspie similarly believed that war was not imminent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Saddam's foreign minister Tariq Aziz later told PBS *Frontline* in 1996 that the Iraqi leadership was under "no illusion" about America's likely response to the Iraqi invasion: "She [Glaspie] didn't tell us anything strange.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] She didn't tell us in the sense that we concluded that the Americans will not retaliate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The result of the Jeddah talks was an Iraqi demand for $10 billion to cover the lost revenues from Rumaila; Kuwait offered $500 million.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraqi response was to immediately order an invasion, which started on 2 August 1990 with the bombing of Kuwait's capital, Kuwait City.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Before the invasion, the Kuwaiti military was believed to have numbered 16,000 men, arranged into three armored, one mechanized infantry and one under-strength artillery brigade.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The pre-war strength of the Kuwait Air Force was around 2,200 Kuwaiti personnel, with 80 fixed-wing aircraft and 40 helicopters.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In spite of Iraqi sabre-rattling, Kuwait did not mobilize its force; the army had been stood-down on 19 July, and during the Iraqi invasion many Kuwaiti military personnel were on leave.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] By 1988, at the end of the Iran–Iraq war, the Iraqi Army was the world's fourth largest army, consisting of 955,000 standing soldiers and 650,000 paramilitary forces in the Popular Army.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] According to John Childs and André Corvisier, a low estimate shows the Iraqi Army capable of fielding 4,500 tanks, 484 combat aircraft and 232 combat helicopters.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraqi commandos infiltrated the Kuwaiti border first to prepare for the major units, which began the attack at midnight.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraqi attack had two prongs, with the primary attack force driving south straight for Kuwait City down the main highway, and a supporting attack force entering Kuwait farther west, but then turning and driving east, cutting off Kuwait City from the country's southern half.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The commander of a Kuwaiti armored battalion, 35th Armoured Brigade, deployed them against the Iraqi attack and conducted a robust defense at the Battle of the Bridges near Al Jahra, west of Kuwait City.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Kuwaiti aircraft scrambled to meet the invading force, but approximately 20% were lost or captured.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A few combat sorties were flown against Iraqi ground forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The main Iraqi thrust into Kuwait City was conducted by commandos deployed by helicopters and boats to attack the city from the sea, while other divisions seized the airports and two airbases.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraqis attacked the Dasman Palace, the Royal Residence of Kuwait's emir, Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, which was defended by the Emiri Guard supported with M-84 tanks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In the process, the Iraqis killed Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, the Emir's youngest brother.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Within 12 hours, most resistance had ended within Kuwait, and the royal family had fled, allowing Iraq to control most of Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After two days of intense combat, most of the Kuwaiti military were either overrun by the Iraqi Republican Guard, or had escaped to Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The emir and key ministers fled south along the highway for refuge in Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraqi ground forces consolidated their control of Kuwait City, then headed south and redeployed along the Saudi border.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After the decisive Iraqi victory, Saddam initially installed a puppet regime known as the "Provisional Government of Free Kuwait" before installing his cousin Ali Hassan al-Majid as Kuwait's governor on 8 August.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After the invasion, the Iraqi military looted over $1 billion in banknotes from Kuwait's Central Bank.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] At the same time, Saddam Hussein made the Kuwaiti dinar equal to the Iraqi dinar, thereby lowering the Kuwaiti currency to one-twelfth of its original value.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In response, Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah ruled the banknotes as invalid and refused to reimburse stolen notes, which became worthless because of a UN embargo.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After the conflict ended, many of the stolen banknotes made their way back into circulation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The stolen banknotes are a collectible for numismatists.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Kuwaitis founded a local armed resistance movement following the Iraqi occupation of Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Kuwaiti resistance's casualty rate far exceeded that of the coalition military forces and Western hostages.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The resistance predominantly consisted of ordinary citizens who lacked any form of training and supervision.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A key element of US political, military and energy economic planning occurred in 1984.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iran–Iraq war had been going on for five years and both had sustained casualties into the hundreds of thousands.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Within President Ronald Reagan's National Security Council concern was growing war could spread beyond the two belligerents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A National Security Planning Group meeting was formed, chaired by then vice president George H.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] It was determined that the conflict would likely spread into Saudi Arabia and other Gulf states, but the US had little capability to defend the region.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A prolonged war in the region would induce much higher oil prices and threaten the recovery of the world economy, which was just beginning to gain momentum.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In May 1984, President Reagan was briefed on the project conclusions by William Flynn Martin who had served as the head of the NSC staff that organized the study.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The plan was approved by Reagan and affirmed by the G7 leaders headed by the UK's prime minister, Margaret Thatcher, in the 10th G7 summit, held in London in June.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The plan was implemented and became the basis for US preparedness to respond to the Iraqi occupation of Kuwait in 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Within hours of the invasion, Kuwait and US delegations requested a meeting of the UN Security Council, which passed Resolution 660, condemning the invasion and demanding a withdrawal of Iraqi troops.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 3 August 1990, the Arab League passed a resolution, which called for a solution from within the league, and warned against outside intervention.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq and Libya were the only Arab League states that opposed the resolution for Iraq to withdraw; the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) opposed it as well.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Yemen and Jordan – a Western ally which bordered Iraq and relied on the country for economic support – opposed military intervention from non-Arab states.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Separately, Sudan, also an Arab League member, aligned itself with Saddam.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 6 August, Resolution 661 placed economic sanctions on Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Resolution 665 followed soon after, which authorized a naval blockade to enforce the sanctions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Once persuaded, US officials insisted on Iraqi pullout, without any linkage to other Middle Eastern problems, accepting the British view that any concession would strengthen Iraqi influence.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 12 August 1990, Saddam "propose[d] that all cases of occupation, and those cases that have been portrayed as occupation, in the region, be resolved simultaneously".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] He requested an "immediate freeze of all boycott and siege decisions" and a normalization of relations with Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Bush was strongly opposed to any "linkage" between Iraq's occupation of Kuwait and the Palestinian issue.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 23 August, Saddam appeared on state television with Western hostages to whom he had refused exit visas.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In the video, he asks a British boy, Stuart Lockwood, whether he is getting his milk, and goes on to say, through his interpreter, "We hope your presence as guests here will not be for too long.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Another Iraqi proposal communicated was delivered to US national security advisor Brent Scowcroft by an unidentified Iraqi official.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On 29 November 1990, the Security Council passed Resolution 678, which gave Iraq until 15 January 1991 to withdraw from Kuwait, and empowered states to use "all necessary means" to force Iraq out of Kuwait after the deadline.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In December 1990, Iraq made a proposal to withdraw from Kuwait provided foreign troops left the region and that an agreement was reached regarding the Palestinian problem and the dismantlement of Israel's and Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The PLO's Yasser Arafat expressed that neither he nor Saddam insisted that solving the Israel–Palestine issues should be a precondition to solving the issues in Kuwait, though he did acknowledge a "strong link" between these problems.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US and UK stuck to their position there would be no negotiations until Iraq withdrew, and should not grant Iraq concessions, lest they give the impression Iraq benefited from its military campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] When US secretary of state James Baker met with Tariq Aziz in Geneva, for last minute peace talks in early 1991, Aziz reportedly made no concrete proposals and did not outline any hypothetical Iraqi moves.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US, UK, and Soviet Union rejected it; US ambassador to the UN Thomas Pickering stated that the French proposal was unacceptable, because it went beyond Council resolutions on the Iraqi invasion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] France dropped this proposal when it found "no tangible sign of interest" from Baghdad.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A concern in the Western world was the significant threat Iraq posed to Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Following Kuwait's conquest, the Iraqi Army was within striking distance of Saudi oil fields.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Control of these, along with Kuwaiti and Iraqi reserves, would have given Saddam control over most of the world's oil reserves.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Saudis had lent Iraq 26 billion dollars during its war with Iran, as the Saudis feared the influence of Shia Iran's Islamic revolution on its own Shia minority.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After the war, Saddam felt he should not have to repay the loans due to the help he had given the Saudis by fighting Iran.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After his conquest of Kuwait, Saddam verbally attacked the Saudis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] He argued the US-supported Saudi state was an illegitimate and unworthy guardian of the holy cities of Mecca and Medina.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] He combined the language of the Islamist groups that had fought in Afghanistan with the rhetoric Iran had used to attack the Saudis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Acting on the Carter Doctrine policy, and out of fear the Iraqi Army could invade Saudi Arabia, Bush announced that the US would launch a "wholly defensive" mission to prevent Iraq from invading Saudi Arabia, under the codename Operation Desert Shield.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The operation began on 7 August 1990, when US troops were sent to Saudi Arabia, due also to the request of its monarch, King Fahd, who had called for US military assistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This "wholly defensive" doctrine was quickly abandoned when, on 8 August, Iraq declared Kuwait to be Iraq's 19th province and Saddam named his cousin, Ali Hassan Al-Majid, as its governor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US Navy dispatched two naval battle groups built around the aircraft carriers USS *Dwight D.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Eisenhower* and USS *Independence* to the Gulf, where they were ready by 8 August.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US sent the battleships USS *Missouri* and USS *Wisconsin*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] 48 US Air Force F-15s from the 1st Fighter Wing at Langley Air Force Base, Virginia, landed in Saudi Arabia and commenced round-the-clock air patrols of the Saudi–Kuwait–Iraq border to discourage Iraqi military advances.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] They were joined by 36 F-15 A-Ds from the 36th Tactical Fighter Wing at Bitburg, Germany.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Bitburg contingent was based at Al Kharj Air Base.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The 36th TFW would be responsible for 11 confirmed Iraqi Air Force aircraft shot down during the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Military buildup continued, reaching 543,000 troops, twice that used in the 2003 invasion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Much of the material was airlifted or carried to the staging areas via fast sealift ships, allowing a quick buildup.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Amphibious exercises were carried out in the Gulf, including Operation Imminent Thunder, which involved the USS *Midway* and 15 other ships, 1,100 aircraft, and a thousand Marines.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In a press conference, General Schwarzkopf stated that these exercises were intended to deceive the Iraqi forces, forcing them to continue their defense of the Kuwaiti coastline.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Resolution 678, passed on 29 November 1990, gave Iraq a withdrawal deadline until 15 January 1991 and authorized "all necessary means to uphold and implement Resolution 660", and a diplomatic formulation authorizing the use of force if Iraq failed to comply.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] To ensure the US received economic backing, James Baker went on an 11-day journey to nine countries in September 1990, which the press dubbed "The Tin Cup Trip".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The first stop was Saudi Arabia, which had already granted permission to the US to use its facilities.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] However, Baker believed that Saudi Arabia should assume some of the cost of to defend it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] When Baker asked King Fahd for $15 billion, the King agreed, with the promise that Baker ask Kuwait for the same amount.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The next day, 7 September, Baker did just that, and the emir of Kuwait, displaced in a Sheraton hotel outside Kuwait, agreed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Baker moved to enter talks with Egypt, whose leadership he considered "the moderate voice of the Middle East".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] President Mubarak was furious with Saddam for his invasion, and that Saddam had assured Mubarak that an invasion was not his intention.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Egypt received approximately $7 billion in debt forgiveness for providing support and troops for the US-led intervention.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After stops in Helsinki and Moscow to smooth out Iraqi demands for a Middle-Eastern peace conference with the Soviet Union, Baker traveled to Syria to discuss its role with President Hafez Assad.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This was a vital step in ensuring Arab states were represented in the coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In exchange, Washington gave al-Assad the green light to wipe out forces opposing Syria's rule in Lebanon and arranged for weapons valued at a billion dollars to be provided to Syria, mostly through Gulf states.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In exchange for Iran's support for the US-led intervention, the US promised Iran to end US opposition to World Bank loans to Iran.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] On the day before the coalition ground invasion, the World Bank gave Iran the first loan of $250m.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Baker flew to Rome for a meeting with the Italians in which he was promised the use of military equipment, before journeying to Germany to meet with American ally Chancellor Kohl.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] It was the largest coalition since World War II.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A group of Afghan mujahideen soldiers also reportedly joined towards the end of the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Although they did not contribute forces, Japan and Germany made financial contributions totaling $10 billion and $6.6 billion respectively.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] US troops represented 73% of the coalition's 956,600 troops in Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] US Army General Norman Schwarzkopf, Jr. was designated to be the commander of the coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Soviet Union condemned Baghdad's aggression against Kuwait, but did not support the US and allied intervention in Iraq and tried to avert it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Many of the coalition countries were reluctant to commit military forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Some felt that the war was an internal Arab affair or did not want to increase US influence in the Middle East.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In the end, however, many governments were persuaded by Iraq's belligerence towards other Arab states, offers of economic aid or debt forgiveness, and threats to withhold aid.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The US and UN gave public justifications for involvement in the conflict, the most prominent being the Iraqi violation of Kuwaiti territorial integrity.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] In addition, the US moved to support its ally Saudi Arabia, whose importance in the region, and as a key supplier of oil, made it of considerable geopolitical importance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Shortly after the Iraqi invasion, US defense secretary Dick Cheney made the first of several visits to Saudi Arabia where King Fahd requested US military assistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] During a speech in a special joint session of the US Congress given on 11 September 1990, Bush summed up the reasons with the following remarks: "Within three days, 120,000 Iraqi troops with 850 tanks had poured into Kuwait and moved south to threaten Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Pentagon stated that satellite photos showing a buildup of Iraqi forces along the border were the source of this information, but this was later alleged to be false.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Petersburg Times* acquired commercial Soviet satellite images which showed nothing but empty desert.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Other justifications for foreign involvement included Iraq's history of human rights abuses under Saddam.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq was known to possess biological weapons and chemical weapons, which Saddam had used against Iranian troops during the Iran–Iraq War and his own country's Kurdish population in the Al-Anfal campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraq was known to have a nuclear weapons program; the report about it from January 1991 was partially declassified by the CIA in May 2001.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Although the Iraqi military committed human rights abuses during the invasion, the alleged incidents that received the most publicity in the US were fabrications of the public relations firm hired by the government of Kuwait to persuade Americans to support military intervention.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Shortly after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, the organization *Citizens for a Free Kuwait* was formed in the US.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] It hired the public relations firm Hill & Knowlton for about $11 million, paid by Kuwait's government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The story helped tip the public and Congress towards a war with Iraq: six Congressmen said the testimony was enough for them to support military action against Iraq and seven Senators referenced the testimony in debate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Senate supported the military actions in a 52–47 vote.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] However, a year after the war, this allegation was revealed to be a fabrication.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The young woman was found to be a member of Kuwait's royal family and the daughter of Kuwait's ambassador to the US.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] She had not lived in Kuwait during the Iraqi invasion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The details of the Hill & Knowlton public relations campaign, including the incubator testimony, were published in John R.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] MacArthur's *Second Front: Censorship and Propaganda in the Gulf War*, and came to public attention when an Op-ed by MacArthur was published in *The New York Times*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] This prompted a reexamination by Amnesty International, which had promoted an account alleging even greater numbers of babies torn from incubators than the fake testimony.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] After finding no evidence to support it, the organization issued a retraction.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Bush repeated the incubator allegations on television.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] The Iraqi Army did commit well-documented crimes during its occupation, such as the summary execution without trial of three brothers, after which their bodies were stacked and left to decay in a street.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Iraqi troops ransacked and looted private homes; one residence was repeatedly defecated in.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] A resident later commented: "The whole thing was violence for the sake of violence, destruction for the sake of destruction ...
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Imagine a surrealistic painting by Salvador Dalí".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p01] Bush repeatedly compared Saddam Hussein to Hitler.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Gulf War began with an extensive aerial bombing campaign on 16 January 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] For 42 consecutive days and nights, the coalition forces subjected Iraq to one of the most intensive air bombardments in military history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The coalition flew over 100,000 sorties, dropping 88,500 tonnes of bombs, which widely destroyed military and civilian infrastructure.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi anti-aircraft defenses, including man-portable air-defense systems, were surprisingly ineffective against enemy aircraft, and the coalition suffered only 75 aircraft losses in over 100,000 sorties, 44 due to Iraqi action.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Two of these losses are the result of aircraft colliding with the ground while evading Iraqi ground-fired weapons.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] One of these losses is a confirmed air-air victory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq's government made no secret that it would attack Israel if invaded.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Prior to the war's start, in the aftermath of the failed US–Iraq peace talks in Geneva, Switzerland, a reporter asked Iraq's English-speaking foreign minister and deputy prime minister Tariq Aziz: "Mr.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Five hours after the first attacks, Iraq's state radio broadcast declared that "The dawn of victory nears as this great showdown begins." Iraq fired eight missiles the next day.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] These missile attacks were to continue throughout the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq fired 88 Scud missiles during the war's seven weeks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq hoped to provoke a military response from Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi government hoped that many Arab states would withdraw from the Coalition, as they would be reluctant to fight alongside Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Following the first attacks, Israeli Air Force jets were deployed to patrol the northern airspace with Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Israel prepared to militarily retaliate, as its policy for the previous 40 years had always been retaliation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] However, President Bush pressured Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Shamir not to retaliate and withdraw Israeli jets, fearing that if Israel attacked Iraq, the other Arab states would either desert the coalition or join Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was also feared that if Israel used Syrian or Jordanian airspace to attack Iraq, they would intervene in the war on Iraq's side or attack Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The coalition promised to deploy Patriot missiles to defend Israel if it refrained from responding to the Scud attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Scud missiles targeting Israel were relatively ineffective, as firing at extreme range resulted in a dramatic reduction in accuracy and payload.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Two Israeli civilians died as a direct result of the missile attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Between 11 and 74 died from incorrect use of gas masks, heart attacks, and incorrect use of the anti-chemical weapons drug atropine.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Approximately 230 Israelis were injured.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] As a result, Israel's government issued gas masks to its citizens.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] When the first Iraqi missiles hit Israel, some people injected themselves with an antidote for nerve gas.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It has been suggested that the sturdy construction techniques used in Israeli cities, coupled with the fact that Scuds were only launched at night, played an important role in limiting the number of casualties from Scud attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In response to the threat of Scuds on Israel, the US rapidly sent a Patriot missile air defense artillery battalion to Israel along with two batteries of MIM-104 Patriot missiles for the protection of civilians.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Royal Netherlands Air Force also deployed a Patriot missile squadron to Israel and Turkey.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Dutch Defense Ministry later stated that the military use of the Patriot missile system was largely ineffective, but its psychological value for the affected populations was high.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Coalition air forces were also extensively exercised in "Scud hunts" in the Iraqi desert, trying to locate the camouflaged trucks before they fired their missiles at Israel or Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On the ground, special operations forces also infiltrated Iraq, tasked with locating and destroying Scuds – including the ill-fated Bravo Two Zero patrol of the SAS.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Once special operations were combined with air patrols, the number of attacks fell sharply, then increased slightly as Iraqi forces adjusted to coalition tactics.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] As the Scud attacks continued, the Israelis grew increasingly impatient, and considered taking unilateral military action against Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 22 January 1991, a Scud missile hit the Israeli city of Ramat Gan, after two coalition Patriots failed to intercept it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Three elderly people suffered fatal heart attacks, another 96 people were injured, and 20 apartment buildings were damaged.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] After this attack, the Israelis warned that if the US failed to stop the attacks, they would.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] At one point, Israeli commandos boarded helicopters prepared to fly into Iraq, but the mission was called off after a phone call from US defense secretary Dick Cheney, reporting on the extent of coalition efforts to destroy Scuds and emphasizing that Israeli intervention could endanger US forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In addition to the attacks on Israel, 47 Scud missiles were fired into Saudi Arabia, and one missile was fired at Bahrain and another at Qatar.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The missiles were fired at both military and civilian targets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] One Saudi civilian was killed, and 78 others were injured.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] No casualties were reported in Bahrain or Qatar.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Saudi government issued all its citizens and expatriates with gas masks in the event of Iraq using missiles with warheads containing chemical weapons.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The government broadcast alerts and 'all clear' messages over television to warn citizens during Scud attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 25 February 1991, a Scud missile hit a US Army barracks of the 14th Quartermaster Detachment, out of Greensburg, Pennsylvania, stationed in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, killing 28 soldiers and injuring over 100.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 29 January, Iraqi forces attacked and occupied the lightly defended Saudi city of Khafji with tanks and infantry.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Battle of Khafji ended two days later when the Iraqis were driven back by the Saudi Arabian National Guard, supported by Qatari forces and US Marines.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The allied forces used extensive artillery fire.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Both sides suffered casualties, although Iraqi forces sustained substantially more dead and captured than the allied forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Eleven Americans were killed in two separate friendly fire incidents, an additional 14 US airmen were killed when their AC-130 gunship was shot down by an Iraqi surface-to-air missile, and two US soldiers were captured during the battle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Saudi and Qatari forces had a total of 18 dead.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi forces in Khafji had 60–300 dead and 400 captured.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Battle of Khafji was an example of how air power could single-handedly hinder the advance of enemy ground forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Upon learning of Iraqi troop movements, 140 coalition aircraft were diverted to attack an advancing column consisting of two armored divisions in battalion-sized units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Precision stand-off attacks were conducted during the night and through to the next day.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi vehicle losses included 357 tanks, 147 armored personnel carriers, and 89 mobile artillery pieces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Some crews simply abandoned their vehicles upon realizing that they could be destroyed by guided bombs, stopping the divisions from massing for an organized attack on the town.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 1-41 Infantry was a US Army heavy battalion task force from the 2nd Armored Division (Forward).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] 2nd Armored Division (Forward) included the 1st Battalion, 41st Infantry Regiment, the 2nd and 3rd Battalions, 66th Armor Regiment, and the 4th Battalion, 3rd Field Artillery Regiment.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 1–41 was the first coalition force to breach the Saudi Arabian border on 15 February 1991, and to conduct ground combat operations in Iraq against the enemy on 17 February 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Shortly after arrival in theatre "..the battalion received, for planning, a brigade cross-boundary counter-reconnaissance mission." 1–41 Infantry was assisted by the 1st Squadron, 4th Armored Cavalry Regiment.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This joint effort would become known as Task Force Iron.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Counter-reconnaissance generally includes destroying or repelling the enemy's reconnaissance elements and denying their commander any observation of friendly forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 15 February 1991 4th Battalion of the 3rd Field Artillery Regiment fired on a trailer and a few trucks in the Iraqi sector observing American forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 16 February 1991 several groups of Iraqi vehicles appeared to be performing reconnaissance on the Task Force and were driven away by fire from 4–3 FA.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Another enemy platoon, including six vehicles, was reported as being to the northeast of the Task Force.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] They were engaged with artillery fire from 4–3 FA.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Later that evening another group of Iraqi vehicles was spotted moving towards the center of the Task Force.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] They appeared to be Iraqi Soviet-made BTRs and tanks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] For the next hour the Task Force fought several small battles with Iraqi reconnaissance units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] TF 1–41 IN fired TOW missiles at the Iraqi formation destroying one tank.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The rest of the formation was destroyed or driven away by artillery fire from 4–3 FA.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 17 February 1991 the Task Force took enemy mortar fire, but the enemy forces managed to escape.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Later that evening the Task Force received enemy artillery fire but suffered no casualties.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] That same evening the Task Force identified an Iraqi mortar position and engaged it with both direct and indirect fires.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis continued probing operations against the Task Force for approximately two hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] For the next two days the Task Force observed Iraqi wheeled vehicles and small units move in front of them.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Several times Iraqi mortars fired on Task Force 1–41 Infantry positions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 18 February Iraqi mortar positions continued to conduct fire missions against the Task Force.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Task Force returned fire on the Iraqi positions with artillery fire from 4–3 FA and 1st Infantry Division Artillery.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] During the Iraqi mortar attacks two American soldiers were wounded.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi reconnaissance elements continued to patrol the area between the Task Force and the 1st Cavalry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] VII Corps air units and artillery conducted combat operations against Iraqi defensive positions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 1–41 Infantry was the first coalition force to breach the Saudi Arabian border on 15 February 1991 and conduct ground combat operations in Iraq engaging in direct and indirect fire fights with the enemy on 17 February 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Prior to this action the Task Force's primary fire support battalion, 4th Battalion of the 3rd Field Artillery Regiment, participated in a massive artillery preparation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Around 300 guns from multiple countries participated in the artillery barrage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Over 14,000 rounds were fired during these missions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] M270 Multiple Launch Rocket Systems contributed an additional 4,900 rockets fired at Iraqi targets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq lost close to 22 artillery battalions during the initial stages of this barrage, including the destruction of approximately 396 Iraqi artillery pieces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] By the end of these raids Iraqi artillery assets had all but ceased to exist.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] One Iraqi unit that was totally destroyed during the preparation was the Iraqi 48th Infantry Division Artillery Group.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The group's commander stated his unit lost 83 of its 100 guns to the artillery preparation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The artillery bombardment was supplemented by Boeing B-52 Stratofortress bombing raids and Lockheed AC-130 attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] AH-64 Apache attack helicopters from the 1st Infantry Division and B-52 bombers attacked the Iraqi 110th Infantry Brigade.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Under enemy fire, the 1st and 9th Engineer Battalions marked and proofed assault lanes to secure a foothold in enemy territory and pass the 1st Infantry Division and the 1st Armoured Division forward.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 24 February 1991 the 1st Cavalry Division fired its artillery against Iraqi artillery units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] One artillery mission struck a series of Iraqi bunkers, reinforced by Iraqi T-55 tanks, in the sector of the Iraqi 25th Infantry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The same day the 2nd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division with the 1st Battalion, 5th Cavalry, 1st Battalion, 32nd Armor, and the 1st Battalion, 8th Cavalry destroyed Iraqi bunkers and combat vehicles in the sector of the Iraqi 25th Infantry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 24 February 2nd Brigade, 1st Infantry Division rolled through the breach in the Iraqi defense west of Wadi al-Batin and also cleared the northeastern sector of the breach site of enemy resistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 3–37th Armor breached the Iraqi defense clearing four passage lanes and expanding the gap under direct enemy fire.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Also on 24 February the 1st Infantry Division along with the 1st Cavalry Division destroyed Iraqi outposts and patrols belonging to the Iraqi 26th Infantry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The two divisions also began capturing prisoners.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Infantry Division cleared a zone between Phase Line Vermont and Phase Line Kansas.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Once the 1st Infantry Division's 3rd Battalion, 37th Armor reached the Iraqi rear defensive positions it destroyed an Iraqi D-30 artillery battery and many trucks and bunkers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 1–41 Infantry was given the task of breaching Iraq's initial defensive positions along the Iraq–Saudi Arabia border.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Squadron, 4th Armored Cavalry Regiment handled similar responsibilities in its sector of operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Infantry Division's 5th Battalion, 16th Infantry also played a significant role clearing the trenches and captured 160 Iraqi soldiers in the process.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Once into Iraqi territory Task Force 1–41 Infantry encountered multiple Iraqi defensive positions and bunkers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] These defensive positions were occupied by a brigade-sized element.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 1–41 Infantry elements dismounted and prepared to engage the enemy soldiers who occupied these well-prepared and heavily fortified bunkers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Task Force found itself engaged in six hours of combat in order to clear the extensive bunker complex.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis engaged the Task Force with small arms fire, RPGs, mortar fire, and what was left of Iraqi artillery assets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A series of battles unfolded resulting in heavy Iraqi casualties and the Iraqis being removed from their defensive positions with many becoming prisoners of war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Some escaped to be killed or captured by other coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In the process of clearing the bunkers, Task Force 1–41 captured two brigade command posts and the command post of the Iraqi 26th Infantry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Task Force also captured a brigade commander, several battalion commanders, company commanders, and staff officers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] As combat operations progressed Task Force 1–41 Infantry engaged at short range multiple dug in enemy tanks in ambush positions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] For a few hours, bypassed Iraqi RPG-equipped anti-tank teams, T-55 tanks, and dismounted Iraqi infantry fired at passing American vehicles, only to be destroyed by other US tanks and fighting vehicles following the initial forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Infantry Division's Task Force 2–16 Infantry cleared four lanes simultaneously through an enemy fortified trench system while inflicting heavy casualties on Iraqi forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Task Force 2–16 continued the attack clearing over 21 km (13 mi) of entrenched enemy positions resulting in the capture and destruction of numerous enemy vehicles, equipment, personnel and command bunkers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A 90,000 round artillery preparation fire on Iraqi defensive positions preceded the major ground assault, lasting 2.5 hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] 1st Infantry Division Artillery, which included 4-3 FA battalion, was decisive during artillery combat operations performing multiple raids and fire missions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] These combat operations resulted in the destruction of 50 enemy tanks, 139 APCs, 30 air defense systems, 152 artillery pieces, 27 missile launchers, 108 mortars, and 548 wheeled vehicles, 61 trench lines and bunker positions, 92 dug in and open infantry targets, and 34 logistical sites.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The ground campaign consisted of three or possibly four of the largest tank battles in American military history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The battles at 73 Easting, Norfolk, and Medina Ridge are well noted for their historical significance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Some consider the Battle of Medina Ridge the largest tank battle of the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Other sources consider the Battle of Norfolk the largest tank battle of the war and the second largest tank battle in American military history, behind the Battle of the Bulge.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Corps also fought the biggest tank battle in its history at Kuwait International Airport.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] 3rd Armored Division also fought a significant battle at Objective Dorset not far from where the Battle of Norfolk was taking place.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] 3rd Armored Division destroyed approximately 300 enemy combat vehicles during this particular encounter with Iraqi forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] VII Corps was the primary combat formation of the coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was a formidable fighting force consisting of 1,487 tanks, 1,384 infantry fighting vehicles, 568 artillery pieces, 132 MLRS, 8 missile launchers, and 242 attack helicopters.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It had a total troop strength of 146,321 troops.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Its primary full strength fighting formations were the 1st Armored Division (United States), the 3rd Armored Division (United States) and the 1st Infantry Division (United States).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 2nd Armored Division (Forward) was assigned to the 1st Infantry Division as its third maneuver brigade.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Its Task Force 1-41 Infantry would be the spearhead of VII Corps.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In addition, the corps had the 2nd Cavalry Regiment (United States) to act as a scouting and screening force, and two further heavy divisions, the 1st Cavalry Division (United States) and the United Kingdom's 1st Armoured Division, as well as the U.S.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] VII Corps fought a number of large battles against Iraqi forces, with some of historic scope and size.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Three of the battles at Norfolk, Medina Ridge, and 73 Easting are considered among the largest tank battles in history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] By the end of combat operations on 28 February 1991, U.S.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] VII Corps had driven 260 kilometres (160 mi), captured 22,000 Iraqi soldiers, and destroyed 1,350 Iraqi tanks, 1,224 armored personnel carriers, 285 artillery pieces, 105 air defense systems, and 1,229 trucks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The primary combat vehicles of the American divisions were the M1A1 Abrams tank and the Bradley Fighting Vehicle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The primary American artillery system was the self propelled M109 howitzer.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The primary American attack helicopter was the Boeing AH-64 Apache (Army) with the Bell AH-1 Cobra (Army and Marines) also being in theatre.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II ground attack aircraft would distinguish itself during the Gulf War aided by the OH-58D JAATT eyes in the sky.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Together they inflicted significant damage on Iraqi ground forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A-10 "Warthog" crews would destroy 900 Iraqi tanks, 2,000 other military vehicles and 1,200 artillery pieces during combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Corps was represented by the 1st Marine Division and the 2nd Marine Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Army's 2nd Armored Division's Tiger Brigade to provide the Marines with additional armor support.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine armor units mostly consisted of the older M-60 tank.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Marine Division destroyed around 60 Iraqi tanks near the Burgan oil field without suffering any losses.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Marine Division Task Force Ripper led the drive to the Kuwait International Airport on 27 February 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Task Force Ripper destroyed about 100 Iraqi tanks and armored personnel carriers, including T-72 tanks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Myatt said, "During the first day of combat operations 1st Platoon, D Company, 3rd Tank Battalion destroyed 15 Iraqi tanks".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Marines also destroyed 25 APCs and took 300 prisoners of war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The U.S.M.C. would often encounter the Iraqi 3rd Armored Division in their theater of operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Once the 1st Marine Division reached Kuwait International Airport they found what remained of the Iraqi 12th Armored Brigade, 3rd Armored Division defending it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Marines destroyed 30 to 40 Iraqi T-72 tanks which had taken up defensive positions around the airport.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 3rd Armored Division losses included more than 250 T-55/62s and 70 T-72 tanks by the end of combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 3rd Armored Division would be totally destroyed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 2nd Marine Division played a major role repelling the attempted Iraqi invasion of Saudi Arabia which is known as the Battle of Khafji.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 2nd Marine Division also faced heavy resistance during the Battle of Kuwait International Airport.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The battle featured the "Reveille Engagement" which went on to become the largest tank battle in United States Marine Corps' entire history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Reserve unit Bravo Company, 4th Tank Battalion, 4th Marine division was assigned to the 2nd Marine Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Bravo Company destroyed a total of 119 enemy vehicles and took over 800 POWs by the end of combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 1st Tank Battalion claimed 50 Iraqi T-55 and T-62 tanks and 25 APCs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 3rd Battalion claimed 57 T-55s and T-62s along with 5 T-72s, 7 APCs, and 10 trucks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 8th Battalion destroyed more than three dozen tanks and a number of other vehicles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Corps armor units would destroy hundreds of Iraqi tanks by the end of combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Marine Corps tank losses would be light as they suffered the loss of ten M-60 tanks during combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The United Kingdom was represented by its 1st Armoured Division known as the Desert Rats.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division fielded approximately 176 Challenger 1 tanks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] British infantry rode into battle on the Warrior tracked armoured vehicle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It had reasonable armour protection and a 30mm gun.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Modified versions of the vehicle included mortar carriers, MILAN antitank systems, and command and control vehicles; and the British possessed a variety of excellent light armoured vehicles built on their FV101 Scorpion chassis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] British artillery was primarily American made M109 howitzers (155mm), M110 howitzers (203mm), and M270 MLRS which were compatible with American systems.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Their air support consisted of Gazelle helicopters, used for reconnaissance, and the Lynx helicopter which was comparable to the American AH-1 Cobra.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British had their full contingent of engineer, logistics, and medical units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division was responsible for protecting the right flank of VII Corps.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was assumed by the Corps' planners the Iraqi 52nd Armored Division would counterattack VII Corps once their penetration into Iraqi defenses was discovered.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division had two brigades (the 4th and 7th) which participated in Operation Granby, the name given to the British military operations during the 1991 Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division had traveled 217 miles in 97 hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division had captured or destroyed about 300 Iraqi tanks and a very large number of armored personnel carriers, trucks, reconnaissance vehicles, etc.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Desert Rats also destroyed multiple Iraqi artillery positions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The division also took over 7,000 Iraqi prisoners of war including two division commanders and two other general officers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The British 1st Armoured Division destroyed or isolated four Iraqi infantry divisions (the 26th, 48th, 31st, and 25th) and overran the Iraqi 52nd Armored Division in several sharp engagements.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 80th Armored Brigade would also fall victim to the British 1st Armoured Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq was represented mostly by its own VII Corps and its Jihad Corps.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Its most notable participants were its elite Republican Guard Divisions Tawakalna, Medina, Hammurabi, and Adnan.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The first three of these had a strength of over 660 tanks, 660 infantry fighting vehicles, and thousands of antitank weapons, self propelled artillery, and other combat systems.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Tawakalna Republican Guard Division was Iraq's most powerful division which included approximately 14,000 soldiers, 220 T-72 tanks, 284 infantry fighting vehicles, 126 artillery pieces, and 18 MLRS.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 52nd Armored Division was also a primary participant.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was a powerful division consisting of 245 tanks and 195 armored fighting vehicles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 10th and 12th Armored Divisions were also present.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The two divisions formed the foundation of the Jihad Corps.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqi 10th Armored Division was considered the best regular division in the Iraqi Army.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It had more modern equipment than the other regular Iraqi units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was equipped with T-72 and T-62 tanks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Overall the primary tank of the Iraqi forces was the T-55 tank.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis fielded them in great numbers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis also had elements of two other independent armored brigades in theatre, those being the 50th and 29th Armored Brigades.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraq would also field multiple Infantry Divisions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis suffered the loss of over 3,000 tanks and over 2,000 other combat vehicles during these battles against the American-led coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It is estimated that Iraqi forces suffered 20,000–50,000 troops killed during combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It is also estimated that over 75,000 Iraqi soldiers were wounded.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Between 80,000 and 175,000 Iraqi troops were taken prisoner.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi forces inflicted very minimal damage on Coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] US decoy attacks by air attacks and naval gunfire the night before Kuwait's liberation were designed to make the Iraqis believe the main coalition ground attack would focus on central Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] For months, American units in Saudi Arabia had been under almost constant Iraqi artillery fire, as well as threats from Scud missiles and chemical attacks.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 24 February 1991, the 1st and 2nd Marine Divisions and the 1st Light Armored Infantry Battalion crossed into Kuwait and headed toward Kuwait City.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] They encountered trenches, barbed wire, and minefields.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] However, these positions were poorly defended, and were overrun in the first few hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Several tank battles took place, but otherwise coalition troops encountered minimal resistance, as most Iraqi troops surrendered.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The general pattern was that the Iraqis would put up a short fight before surrendering.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] However, Iraqi air defenses shot down nine US aircraft.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Meanwhile, forces from Arab states advanced into Kuwait from the east, encountering little resistance and suffering few casualties.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Despite the successes of coalition forces, it was feared that the Iraqi Republican Guard would escape into Iraq before it could be destroyed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was decided to send British armored forces into Kuwait 15 hours ahead of schedule, and to send US forces after the Republican Guard.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The coalition advance was preceded by a heavy artillery and rocket barrage, after which 150,000 troops and 1,500 tanks began their advance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi forces in Kuwait counterattacked against US troops, acting on a direct order from Saddam Hussein himself.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Despite the intense combat, the Americans repulsed the Iraqis and continued to advance towards Kuwait City.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Kuwaiti forces were tasked with liberating the city.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi troops offered only light resistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Kuwaitis quickly liberated the city despite losing one soldier and having one plane shot down.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 27 February, Saddam ordered a retreat from Kuwait, and President Bush declared it liberated.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] However, an Iraqi unit at Kuwait International Airport appeared not to have received the message and fiercely resisted.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] US Marines fought for hours before securing the airport, after which Kuwait was declared secure.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] After four days of fighting, Iraqi forces were expelled from Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] As part of a scorched earth policy, they set fire to nearly 700 oil wells and placed land mines around the wells to make extinguishing the fires more difficult.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The war's ground phase was officially designated Operation Desert Saber.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The first units to move into Iraq were three patrols of the British Special Air Service's B squadron, call signs Bravo One Zero, Bravo Two Zero, and Bravo Three Zero, in late January.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] These eight-man patrols landed behind Iraqi lines to gather intelligence on the movements of Scud mobile missile launchers, which could not be detected from the air, as they were hidden under bridges and camouflage netting during the day.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Other objectives included the destruction of the launchers and their fiber-optic communications arrays that lay in pipelines and relayed coordinates to the TEL operators launching attacks against Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The operations were designed to prevent any possible Israeli intervention.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Due to lack of sufficient ground cover to carry out their assignment, One Zero and Three Zero abandoned their operations, while Two Zero remained, and was later compromised, with only Sergeant Chris Ryan escaping to Syria.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Elements of the 2nd Brigade, 1st Battalion 5th Cavalry of the 1st Cavalry Division of the US Army performed a direct attack into Iraq on 15 February 1991, followed by one in force on 20 February that led directly through seven Iraqi divisions which were caught off guard.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 17 January 1991 the 101st Airborne Division Aviation Regiment fired the first shots of the war when eight AH-64 helicopters successfully destroyed two Iraqi early warning radar sites.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] From 15 to 20 February, the Battle of Wadi al-Batin took place inside Iraq; this was the first of two attacks by 1 Battalion 5th Cavalry of the 1st Cavalry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was a feint attack, designed to make the Iraqis think that a coalition invasion would take place from the south.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis fiercely resisted, and the Americans eventually withdrew as planned back into the Wadi al-Batin.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Three US soldiers were killed and nine wounded, with one M2 Bradley IFV turret destroyed, but they had taken 40 prisoners and destroyed five tanks, and successfully deceived the Iraqis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This attack led the way for the XVIII Airborne Corps to sweep around behind the 1st Cav and attack Iraqi forces to the west.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 22 February 1991, Iraq agreed to a Soviet-proposed ceasefire agreement.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The agreement called for Iraq to withdraw troops to pre-invasion positions within six weeks following a total ceasefire, and called for monitoring of the ceasefire and withdrawal to be overseen by the UN Security Council.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The coalition rejected the proposal, but said that retreating Iraqi forces would not be attacked, and gave 24 hours for Iraq to withdraw its forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 23 February, fighting resulted in the capture of 500 Iraqi soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 24 February, British and American armored forces crossed the Iraq–Kuwait border and entered Iraq in large numbers, taking hundreds of prisoners.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Iraqi resistance was light, and four Americans were killed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Shortly afterwards, the US VII Corps, in full strength and spearheaded by the 2nd Armored Cavalry Regiment, launched an armored attack into Iraq early on 24 February, just to the west of Kuwait, surprising Iraqi forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Simultaneously, the US XVIII Airborne Corps launched a sweeping "left-hook" attack across southern Iraq's largely undefended desert, led by the US 3rd Armored Cavalry Regiment and the 24th Infantry Division (Mechanized).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This movement's left flank was protected by the French Division Daguet.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 101st Airborne Division conducted a combat air assault into enemy territory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 101st Airborne Division had struck 249 km (155 mi) behind enemy lines.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It was the deepest air assault operation in history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Approximately 400 helicopters transported 2,000 soldiers into Iraq where they destroyed Iraqi columns trying to flee westward and prevented the escape of Iraqi forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 101st Airborne Division travelled a further 80 to 100 km (50 to 60 mi) into Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] By nightfall, the 101st cut off Highway 8 which was a vital supply line running between Basra and the Iraqi forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The 101st had lost 16 soldiers in action during the 100-hour war and captured thousands of enemy prisoners of war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The French force quickly overcame Iraq's 45th Infantry Division, suffering light casualties and taking a large number of prisoners, and took up blocking positions to prevent an Iraqi counterattack on the coalition's flank.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The movement's right flank was protected by the United Kingdom's 1st Armoured Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Once the allies had penetrated deep into Iraqi territory, they turned eastward, launching a flank attack against the elite Republican Guard before it could escape.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis resisted fiercely from dug-in positions and stationary vehicles, and even mounted armored charges.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Unlike many previous engagements, the destruction of the first Iraqi tanks did not result in a mass surrender.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Iraqis suffered massive losses and lost dozens of tanks and vehicles, while US casualties were comparatively low, with a single Bradley knocked out.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Coalition forces pressed another 10 km (6.2 mi) into Iraqi territory, and captured their objective within three hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] They took 500 prisoners and inflicted heavy losses, defeating Iraq's 26th Infantry Division.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A US soldier was killed by an Iraqi land mine, another five by friendly fire, and 30 wounded during the battle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Meanwhile, British forces attacked Iraq's Medina Division and a major Republican Guard logistics base.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In nearly two days of some of the war's most intense fighting, the British destroyed 40 enemy tanks and captured a division commander.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Meanwhile, US forces attacked the village of Al Busayyah, meeting fierce resistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The US force destroyed military hardware and took prisoners, while suffering no casualties.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 25 February 1991, Iraqi forces fired a Scud missile at an American barracks in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The missile attack killed 28 US military personnel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The coalition's advance was much swifter than US generals had expected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 26 February, after setting 737 of Kuwait's oil wells on fire, Iraqi troops began retreating.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A long convoy of retreating Iraqi troops formed along the main Iraq–Kuwait highway.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This convoy was bombed so extensively by coalition air forces that it came to be known as the Highway of Death.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] American, British, and French forces continued to pursue retreating Iraqi forces over the border and back into Iraq, eventually moving to within 240 km (150 mi) of Baghdad, before withdrawing back to Iraq's border with Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In coalition-occupied Iraqi territory, a peace conference was held where a ceasefire agreement was negotiated and signed by both sides.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] At the conference, Iraq was authorized to fly armed helicopters on their side of the temporary border, ostensibly for government transit due to the damage done to civilian infrastructure.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Soon after, these helicopters and much of Iraq's military were used to fight an uprising in the south.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On March 1, 1991, one day after the Gulf War ceasefire, a revolt broke out in Basra against the Iraqi government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The uprising spread within days to all of the largest Shia cities in southern Iraq: Najaf, Amarah, Diwaniya, Hilla, Karbala, Kut, Nasiriyah and Samawah.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The rebellions were encouraged by an airing of "The Voice of Free Iraq" on 24 February 1991, which was broadcast from a CIA-run radio station out of Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Arabic service of the Voice of America supported the uprising by stating that the rebellion was well supported, and that they would soon be liberated from Saddam.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In the north, Kurdish leaders took American statements that they would support an uprising to heart, and began fighting, hoping to trigger a coup d'état.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] However, when no US support came, Iraqi generals remained loyal to Saddam and brutally crushed the Kurdish uprising and the uprising in the south.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Millions of Kurds fled across the mountains to Turkey and Kurdish areas of Iran.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On April 5, the Iraqi government announced "the complete crushing of acts of sedition, sabotage and rioting in all towns of Iraq." An estimated 25,000 to 100,000 Iraqis were killed in the uprisings.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In Kuwait, the Emir was restored, and suspected Iraqi collaborators were repressed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Eventually, over 400,000 people were expelled from the country, including a large number of Palestinians, because of PLO support of Saddam.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Yasser Arafat did not apologize for his support of Iraq, but after his death Mahmoud Abbas formally apologized in 2004 on behalf of the PLO.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This came after the Kuwaiti government formally forgave the group.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] There was some criticism of the Bush administration, as they chose to allow Saddam to remain in power instead of pushing on to capture Baghdad and overthrowing his government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In their co-written 1998 book, *A World Transformed*, Bush and Brent Scowcroft argued that such a course would have fractured the alliance, and would have had many unnecessary political and human costs associated with it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] On 15 March 1991, Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah returned to Kuwait, staying at the private home of a wealthy Kuwaiti as his own palace had been destroyed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] He was met with a symbolic arrival with several dozen cars filled with people honking their horns and waving Kuwaiti flags who tried to follow the emir's convoy.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] According to *The New York Times*, he faced a population divided between those who stayed and those who fled, a government straining to reassert control and a rejuvenated opposition pressing for greater democracy and other postwar changes, including voting rights for women.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Democracy advocates had been calling for restoration of Parliament that the emir had suspended in 1986.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Germany and Japan provided financial assistance and donated military hardware, although they did not send direct military assistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This later became known as *checkbook diplomacy*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Australia contributed a Naval Task Group, which formed part of the multi-national fleet in the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman, under Operation Damask.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In addition, medical teams were deployed aboard a US hospital ship, and a naval clearance diving team took part in de-mining Kuwait's port facilities following the end of combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Australian Task Force was also placed at great risk with regard to the sea mine threat, with HMAS *Brisbane* narrowly avoiding a mine.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Australians played a significant role in enforcing the sanctions put in place against Iraq following Kuwait's invasion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Following the war's end, Australia deployed a medical unit on Operation Habitat to northern Iraq as part of Operation Provide Comfort.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Argentina was the only South American country to participate in the 1991 Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] It sent a destroyer, ARA Almirante Brown (D-10), a corvette, ARA Spiro (P-43) (later replaced by another corvette, ARA Rosales (P-42)) and a supply ship, ARA *Bahía San Blas* (B-4) to participate on the United Nations blockade and sea control effort of the Persian Gulf.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The success of "Operación Alfil" (English: "Operation Bishop") with more than 700 interceptions and 25,000 nautical miles (46,000 km) sailed in the theatre of operations helped to overcome the so-called "Malvinas syndrome".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Argentina was later classified by the US as a major non-NATO ally due to its contributions during the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Canada was one of the first countries to condemn Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, and it quickly agreed to join the US-led coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In August 1990, Prime Minister Brian Mulroney committed the Canadian Forces to deploy a Naval Task Group.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The destroyers HMCS *Terra Nova* and HMCS *Athabaskan* joined the maritime interdiction force supported by the supply ship HMCS *Protecteur* in Operation Friction.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Canadian Task Group led the coalition's maritime logistics forces in the Persian Gulf.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A fourth ship, HMCS *Huron*, arrived in-theater after hostilities had ceased and was the first allied ship to visit Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Following the UN-authorized use of force against Iraq, the Canadian Forces deployed a CF-18 Hornet and CH-124 Sea King squadron with support personnel, as well as a field hospital to deal with casualties from the ground war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] When the air war began, the CF-18s were integrated into the coalition force and provided air cover and attacked ground targets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] This was the first time since the Korean War that the Canadian Armed Forces had participated in an offensive.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The only CF-18 Hornet to record an official victory during the conflict was an aircraft involved in the beginning of the Battle of Bubiyan against the Iraqi Navy.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The second largest European contingent was from France, which committed 18,000 troops.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Operating on the left flank of the US XVIII Airborne Corps, the French Army force was the Division Daguet, including troops from the French Foreign Legion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Initially, the French operated independently under national command and control, but coordinated closely with the Americans (via CENTCOM) and Saudis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] In January, the Division was placed under the tactical control of the XVIII Airborne Corps.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] France also deployed several combat aircraft and naval units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The French called their contribution Opération Daguet.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] During the 42 days of war, Italian fighters made 226 sorties for a total of 589 flight hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The Italian Air Force recorded the loss of a single aircraft in the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The use of Italian aircraft as part of the Desert Storm operation represented the first operational employment in combat missions of Italian Air Force aircraft since the end of World War II.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The United Kingdom committed the largest contingent of any European state that participated in the war's combat operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Operation Granby was the code name for the operations in the Persian Gulf.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] British Army regiments (mainly with the 1st Armoured Division), Royal Air Force, Naval Air Squadrons and Royal Navy vessels were mobilized in the Persian Gulf.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Both Royal Air Force and Naval Air Squadrons, using various aircraft, operated from airbases in Saudi Arabia and Naval Air Squadrons from various vessels in the Persian Gulf.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The United Kingdom played a major role in the Battle of Norfolk, where its forces destroyed over 200 Iraqi tanks and a large quantity of other vehicles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] After 48 hours of combat the British 1st Armoured Division destroyed or isolated four Iraqi infantry divisions (the 26th, 48th, 31st, and 25th) and overran the Iraqi 52nd Armored Division in several sharp engagements.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] Chief Royal Navy vessels deployed to the Persian Gulf included *Broadsword*-class frigates, and *Sheffield*-class destroyers; other R.N. and RFA ships were also deployed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] The light aircraft carrier HMS *Ark Royal* was deployed to the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p02] A British Challenger 1 achieved the longest range confirmed tank kill of the war, destroying an Iraqi tank with an armour-piercing fin-stabilized discarding-sabot (APFSDS) round fired over 4,700 metres (2.9 mi)—the longest tank-on-tank kill shot ever recorded.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Over 1,000 Kuwaiti civilians were killed by Iraqis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] More than 600 Kuwaitis went missing during Iraq's occupation, and approximately 375 remains were found in mass graves in Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The increased importance of air attacks from both coalition warplanes and cruise missiles led to controversy over the number of civilian deaths caused during Desert Storm's initial stages.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Within Desert Storm's first 24 hours, more than 1,000 sorties were flown, many against targets in Baghdad.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In one noted incident, two USAF stealth planes bombed a bunker in Amiriyah, killing 408 Iraqi civilians.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Iraqi government claimed that 2,300 civilians died during the air campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A Project on Defense Alternatives study found that 3,664 Iraqi civilians were killed in the conflict.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] During the nationwide uprisings against the Ba'athist Iraqi government that directly followed the end of the Gulf War in March and April, an estimated 25,000 to 100,000 Iraqis were killed, overwhelmingly civilians.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A Harvard University study released in June 1991 predicted that there would be tens of thousands of additional Iraqi civilian deaths by the end of 1991 due to the "public health catastrophe" caused by the destruction of the country's electrical generating capacity.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] "Without electricity, hospitals cannot function, perishable medicines spoil, water cannot be purified and raw sewage cannot be processed,".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The US government refused to release its own study of the effects of the Iraqi public health crisis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] An investigation in 1992 by Beth Osborne Daponte estimated about 13,000 civilians were directly killed in the war, while another 70,000 died indirectly from the war's other effects.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] According to a 1992 study published in The New England Journal of Medicine by researchers known as the International Study Team (IST), child mortality increased threefold as a result of the war, with 46,900 children under the age of 5 dying between January and August 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Iraq also launched numerous attacks on civilian targets in Israel and Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A 1991 report by Middle East Watch said that at least one Saudi civilian was killed after they were hit by Iraqi shelling in Riyadh.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A disputed number of people were also killed during the Iraqi rocket attacks on Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A United Nations report in March 1991 described the effect on Iraq of the US-led bombing campaign as "near apocalyptic", bringing back Iraq to the "pre-industrial age".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The exact number of Iraqi combat casualties is unknown, but is believed to have been heavy.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Some estimate that Iraq sustained between 20,000 and 35,000 fatalities.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A report commissioned by the US Air Force estimated 10,000–12,000 Iraqi combat deaths in the air campaign, and as many as 10,000 casualties in the ground war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] According to the Project on Defense Alternatives study, between 20,000 and 26,000 Iraqi military personnel were killed in the conflict while 75,000 others were wounded.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A figure was supported by Israeli sources who speak of "one to two hundred thousand Iraqi casualties." Most of the killing "took place during the ground war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The US Department of Defense reports that US forces suffered 148 battle-related deaths (35 to friendly fire), with one pilot listed as MIA (his remains were found and identified in August 2009).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A further 145 Americans died in non-combat accidents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The UK suffered 47 deaths (nine to friendly fire, all by US forces), France nine, and the other countries, not including Kuwait, suffered 37 deaths (18 Saudis, one Egyptian, six UAE and three Qataris).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] At least 605 Kuwaiti soldiers were still missing 10 years after their capture.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The largest single loss of life among coalition forces happened on 25 February 1991, when an Iraqi Al Hussein missile hit a US military barrack in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, killing 28 US Army Reservists from Pennsylvania.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In all, 190 coalition troops were killed by Iraqi fire during the war, 113 of whom were American, out of 358 coalition deaths.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Another 44 soldiers were killed and 57 wounded by friendly fire.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] 145 soldiers died of exploding munitions or non-combat accidents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The largest accident among coalition forces happened on 21 March 1991, when a Royal Saudi Air Force C-130H crashed in heavy smoke on approach to Ras Al-Mishab Airport, Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] 92 Senegalese soldiers and six Saudi crew members were killed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The number of coalition wounded in combat was 776, including 458 Americans.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] 190 coalition troops were killed by Iraqi combatants, the rest of the 379 coalition deaths were from friendly fire or accidents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] This number was much lower than expected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Among the American combat dead were four female soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] While the death toll among coalition forces engaging Iraqi combatants was very low, a substantial number of deaths were caused by accidental attacks from other Allied units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Of the 148 US troops who died in battle, 24% were killed by friendly fire, a total of 35 service personnel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A further 11 died in detonations of coalition munitions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Nine British military personnel were killed in a friendly fire incident when a USAF A-10 Thunderbolt II destroyed a group of two Warrior IFVs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Many returning coalition soldiers reported illnesses following their action in the war, a phenomenon known as Gulf War syndrome (GWS) or Gulf War illness (GWI).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Common symptoms reported are chronic fatigue, fibromyalgia, and gastrointestinal disorder.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] There has been widespread speculation and disagreement about the causes of the illness and the possibly related birth defects.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Researchers found that infants born to male veterans of the 1991 war had higher rates of two types of heart valve defects.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Some children born after the war to Gulf War veterans had a certain kidney defect that was not found in Gulf War veterans' children born before the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Researchers have said that they did not have enough information to link birth defects with exposure to toxic substances.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In 1994, the US Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs with Respect to Export Administration published a report entitled, "U.S.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Chemical and Biological Warfare-Related Dual Use Exports to Iraq and their Possible Impact on the Health Consequences of the Gulf War".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Haley of the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, *et al.*, of 1,016 U.S.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Gulf War veterans found evidence of a causal link between GWS and exposure to low levels of the nerve agent sarin, which was released into the air by coalition bombing of Iraqi chemical weapons facilities.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] By contrast, GWS was *inversely* associated with higher levels of the type Q isozyme, which is more efficient at breaking down sarin than its type R counterpart.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The authors "found that the PON1 genotype and hearing nerve agent alarms were independent and the findings robust to both measured and unmeasured confounding, supporting a mechanistic [gene–environment] interaction. ...
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Moreover, the change in the combined effect from one category to the next was significantly greater than the sum of the independent effects of the environmental exposure and the genotype".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The US military used depleted uranium in tank kinetic energy penetrators and 20–30 mm (0.79–1.18 in) cannon ordnance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Significant controversy regarding the long term safety of depleted uranium exists, including claims of pyrophoric, genotoxic, and teratogenic heavy metal effects.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Many have cited its use during the war as a contributing factor to a number of major health issues in veterans and in surrounding civilian populations, including in birth defects and child cancer rates.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Scientific opinion on the risk is mixed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In 2004, Iraq had the highest mortality rate due to leukemia of any country.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Depleted uranium has 40% less radioactivity than natural uranium.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Depleted uranium is not a significant health hazard unless it is taken into the body.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] External exposure to radiation from depleted uranium is generally not a major concern because the alpha particles emitted by its isotopes travel only a few centimeters in air or can be stopped by a sheet of paper.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Also, the uranium-235 that remains in depleted uranium emits only a small amount of low-energy gamma radiation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] However, if allowed to enter the body, depleted uranium, like natural uranium, has the potential for both chemical and radiological toxicity with the two important target organs being the kidneys and the lungs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In the night of 26–27 February 1991, some Iraqi forces began leaving Kuwait on the main highway north of Al Jahra in a column of some 1,400 vehicles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A patrolling E-8 Joint STARS aircraft observed the retreating forces and relayed the information to the DDM-8 air operations center in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] These vehicles and the retreating soldiers were subsequently attacked by two A-10 aircraft, resulting in a 60 kilometres (37 mi) stretch of highway strewn with debris—the Highway of Death.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] *New York Times* reporter Maureen Dowd wrote, "With the Iraqi leader facing military defeat, Mr.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Another incident during the war highlighted the question of large-scale Iraqi combat deaths.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] This was the "bulldozer assault", wherein two brigades from the US 1st Infantry Division (Mechanized) were faced with a large and complex trench network, as part of the heavily fortified "Saddam Hussein Line".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] After some deliberation, they opted to use anti-mine plows mounted on tanks and combat earthmovers to simply plow over and bury alive the defending Iraqi soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Not a single American was killed during the attack.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Reporters were banned from witnessing the attack, near the neutral zone that touches the border between Saudi Arabia and Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Every American in the assault was inside an armored vehicle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Patrick Day Sloyan of *Newsday* reported, "Bradley Fighting Vehicles and Vulcan armored carriers straddled the trench lines and fired into the Iraqi soldiers as the tanks covered them with mounds of sand.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] 'I came through right after the lead company,' [Col.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] 'What you saw was a bunch of buried trenches with peoples' arms and things sticking out of them.'" However, after the war, the Iraqi government said that only 44 bodies were found.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In his book *The Wars Against Saddam*, John Simpson alleges that US forces attempted to cover up the incident.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In the report, Cheney acknowledged that 457 enemy soldiers were buried during the ground war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A Palestinian exodus from Kuwait took place during and after the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] During the Gulf War, more than 200,000 Palestinians fled Kuwait during the Iraqi occupation of Kuwait due to harassment and intimidation by Iraqi security forces, in addition to getting fired from work by Iraqi authority figures in Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] After the Gulf War, the Kuwaiti authorities forcibly pressured nearly 200,000 Palestinians to leave Kuwait in 1991.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Kuwait's policy, which led to this exodus, was a response to alignment of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and the PLO with Saddam Hussein.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Palestinians who fled Kuwait were Jordanian citizens.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In 2013, 280,000 Jordanian citizens of Palestinian origin lived in Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In 2012, 80,000 Palestinians (without Jordanian citizenship) lived in Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Saudi Arabia expelled Yemeni workers after Yemen supported Saddam during the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] However, the UN subsequently spent billions rebuilding hospitals, schools, and water purification facilities throughout the country.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] During the conflict, coalition aircrew shot down over Iraq were displayed as prisoners of war on TV, most with visible signs of abuse.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Amongst several testimonies to poor treatment, USAF Captain Richard Storr was allegedly tortured by Iraqis during the Persian Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Iraqi secret police broke his nose, dislocated his shoulder and punctured his eardrum.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Royal Air Force Tornado crew John Nichol and John Peters have both alleged that they were tortured during this time.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Nichol and Peters were forced to make statements against the war on television.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Members of British Special Air Service Bravo Two Zero were captured while providing information about an Iraqi supply line of Scud missiles to coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Only one, Chris Ryan, evaded capture while the group's other surviving members were violently tortured.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Flight surgeon (later General) Rhonda Cornum was sexually assaulted by one of her captors after the Black Hawk helicopter in which she was riding was shot down while searching for a downed F-16 pilot.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Since the war, the US has had a continued presence of 5,000 troops stationed in Saudi Arabia – a figure that rose to 10,000 during the 2003 conflict in Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Operation Southern Watch enforced the no-fly zones over southern Iraq set up after 1991; oil exports through the Persian Gulf's shipping lanes were protected by the Bahrain-based US Fifth Fleet.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Since Saudi Arabia houses Mecca and Medina, Islam's holiest sites, many Muslims were upset at the permanent military presence.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Osama bin Laden interpreted the Islamic prophet Muhammad as banning the "permanent presence of infidels in Arabia".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In 1996, bin Laden issued a fatwa, calling for US troops to leave Saudi Arabia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] In a December 1999 interview with Rahimullah Yusufzai, bin Laden said he felt that Americans were "too near to Mecca" and considered this a provocation to the entire Islamic world.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] From 1991 until 2003, the effects of government policy and sanctions regime led to hyperinflation, widespread poverty and malnutrition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] During the late 1990s, the UN considered relaxing the sanctions imposed because of the hardships suffered by ordinary Iraqis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Studies dispute the number of people who died in south and central Iraq during the years of the sanctions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The draining of the Qurna Marshes was an irrigation project in Iraq during and immediately after the war, to drain a large area of marshes in the Tigris–Euphrates river system.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Formerly covering an area of around 3,000 km2 (1,200 sq mi), the large complex of wetlands were nearly emptied of water, and the local Shi'ite population relocated, following the war and 1991 uprisings.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] By 2000, the United Nations Environment Programme estimated that 90% of the marshlands had disappeared, causing desertification of over 7,500 square miles (19,000 km2).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The draining occurred in Iraq and to a smaller degree in Iran between the 1950s and 1990s to clear large areas of the marshes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Formerly covering an area of around 20,000 km2 (7,700 sq mi), the large complex of wetlands was 90% drained before the 2003 Invasion of Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The marshes are typically divided into three main sub-marshes, the Hawizeh, Central, and Hammar Marshes and all three were drained at different times for different reasons.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Initial draining of the Central Marshes was intended to reclaim land for agriculture but later all three marshes would become a tool of war and revenge.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Many international organizations such as the UN Human Rights Commission, the Islamic Supreme Council of Iraq, the Wetlands International, and Middle East Watch have described the project as a political attempt to force the Marsh Arabs out of the area through water diversion tactics.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] On 23 January, Iraq dumped 400 million US gallons (1,500,000 m3) of crude oil into the Persian Gulf, causing the largest offshore oil spill in history at that time.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] It was reported as a deliberate natural resources attack to keep US Marines from coming ashore (*Missouri* and *Wisconsin* had shelled Failaka Island during the war to reinforce the idea that there would be an amphibious assault attempt).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] About 30–40% of this came from allied raids on Iraqi coastal targets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Kuwaiti oil fires were caused by the Iraqi military setting fire to 700 oil wells as part of a scorched earth policy while retreating from Kuwait in 1991 after conquering the country but being driven out by coalition forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The fires started in January and February 1991, and the last one was extinguished by November.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The resulting fires burned uncontrollably because of the dangers of sending in firefighting crews.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Land mines had been placed in areas around the oil wells, and a military cleaning of the areas was necessary before the fires could be put out.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Somewhere around 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) of oil were lost each day.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Eventually, privately contracted crews extinguished the fires, at a total cost of US$1.5 billion to Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] By that time, however, the fires had burned for approximately 10 months, causing widespread pollution.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The 1991 Iraqi uprisings were ethnic and religious uprisings against Saddam Hussein's Ba'athist regime that were mainly led by Shia rebels and Kurds.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The uprisings lasted from March to April 1991 after a ceasefire following the end of the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The mostly uncoordinated insurgency was fueled by the perception that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein had become vulnerable to regime change.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] This perception of weakness was largely the result of the outcome of the Iran–Iraq War and the Gulf War, both of which occurred within a single decade and devastated the population and economy of Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Within the first two weeks, most of Iraq's cities and provinces fell to rebel forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Participants in the uprising were of diverse ethnic, religious and political affiliations, including military mutineers, Shia Islamists, Kurdish nationalists, Kurdish Islamists, and far-left groups.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Following initial victories, the revolution was held back from continued success by internal divisions as well as a lack of anticipated American and Iranian support.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Saddam's Sunni Arab-dominated Ba'ath Party regime managed to maintain control over the capital of Baghdad and soon largely suppressed the rebels in a brutal campaign conducted by loyalist forces spearheaded by the Iraqi Republican Guard.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] During the brief, roughly one-month period of unrest, tens of thousands of people died and nearly two million people were displaced.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] After the conflict, the Iraqi government intensified a prior systematic forced relocation of Marsh Arabs and the draining of the Mesopotamian Marshes in the Tigris–Euphrates river system.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Gulf War Coalition established Iraqi no-fly zones over northern and southern Iraq, and the Kurdish opposition established the Kurdistan Region in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) was an inspection regime created by the United Nations to ensure Iraq's compliance with policies concerning Iraqi production and use of weapons of mass destruction after the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Between 1991 and 1997 its director was Rolf Ekéus; from 1997 to 1999 its director was Richard Butler.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The cost of the war to the United States was calculated by the US Congress in April 1992 to be $61.1 billion (equivalent to $122 billion in 2024).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] About $52 billion of that amount was paid by other countries: $36 billion by Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Arab states of the Persian Gulf; $16 billion by Germany and Japan (which sent no combat forces due to their constitutions).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] About 25% of Saudi Arabia's contribution was paid with in-kind services to the troops, such as food and transportation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] US troops represented about 74% of the combined force, and the global cost was therefore higher.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Apart from the impact on Arab States of the Persian Gulf, the resulting economic disruptions after the crisis affected many states.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Overseas Development Institute (ODI) undertook a study in 1991 to assess the effects on developing states and the international community's response.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] A briefing paper finalized on the day that the conflict ended draws on their findings which had two main conclusions: Many developing states were severely affected and while there has been a considerable response to the crisis, the distribution of assistance was highly selective.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The ODI factored in elements of "cost" which included oil imports, remittance flows, re-settlement costs, loss of export earnings and tourism.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] For Egypt, the cost totaled $1 billion, 3% of GDP.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Yemen had a cost of $830 million, 10% of GDP, while it cost Jordan $1.8 billion, 32% of GDP.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] International response to the crisis on developing states came with the channeling of aid through The Gulf Crisis Financial Co-ordination Group.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] They were 24 states, comprising most of the OECD countries plus some Gulf states: Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Qatar and Kuwait.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The members of this group agreed to disperse $14 billion in development assistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The World Bank responded by speeding up the disbursement of existing project and adjustment loans.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The International Monetary Fund adopted two lending facilities – the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) and the Compensatory & Contingency Financing Facility (CCFF).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The European Community offered $2 billion in assistance.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] US policy regarding media freedom was much more restrictive than in the Vietnam War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The policy had been spelled out in a Pentagon document entitled *Annex Foxtrot*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Most of the press information came from briefings organized by the military.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Only selected journalists were allowed to visit the front lines or conduct interviews with soldiers.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Those visits were always conducted in the presence of officers, and were subject to both prior approval by the military and censorship afterward.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] This was ostensibly to protect sensitive information from being revealed to Iraq.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] This policy was heavily influenced by the military's experience with the Vietnam War, in which public opposition within the US grew throughout the war's course.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] It was not only the limitation of information in the Middle East; media were also restricting what was shown about the war with more graphic depictions like Ken Jarecke's image of a burnt Iraqi soldier being pulled from the American AP wire whereas in Europe it was given extensive coverage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Two BBC journalists, John Simpson and Bob Simpson (no relation), defied their editors and remained in Baghdad to report on the war's progress.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Alternative media outlets provided views opposing the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Deep Dish Television compiled segments from independent producers in the US and abroad, and produced a 10-hour series that was distributed internationally, called The Gulf Crisis TV Project.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The series' first program *War, Oil and Power* was compiled and released in 1990, before the war broke out.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] *News World Order* was the title of another program in the series; it focused on the media's complicity in promoting the war, as well as Americans' reactions to the media coverage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Media watchdog group Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting (FAIR) critically analyzed media coverage during the war in various articles and books, such as the 1991 *Gulf War Coverage: The Worst Censorship was at Home*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Gulf War was notable for some of the first large-scale uses of precision-guided munitions, and stealth aircraft, via the Lockheed F-117 Nighthawk.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Analysts refer to it as the "first space war" for the US usage of satellite-based reconnaissance, communications, and navigation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Precision-guided munitions, informally "smart bombs", were heralded as key in allowing military strikes to be made with a minimum of civilian casualties compared to previous wars, although they were not used as often as more traditional, less accurate bombs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Specific buildings in downtown Baghdad could be bombed while journalists in their hotels watched cruise missiles fly by.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Precision-guided munitions amounted to approximately 7.4% of all bombs dropped by the coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Other bombs included cluster bombs, which disperse numerous submunitions, and daisy cutters, 15,000-pound bombs which can disintegrate everything within hundreds of yards.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Global Positioning System (GPS) units were relatively new at the time and were important in enabling coalition units to easily navigate across the desert.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Since military GPS receivers were not available for most troops, many used commercially available units.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] To permit these to be used to best effect, the "selective availability" feature of the GPS system was turned off for the duration of Desert Storm, allowing these commercial receivers to provide the same precision as the military equipment.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Airborne Warning and Control System (AWACS) and satellite communication systems were also important.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Two examples of this are the US Navy's Grumman E-2 Hawkeye and the US Air Force's Boeing E-3 Sentry.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Both were used in command and control area of operations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] These systems provided essential communications links between air, ground, and naval forces.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] It is one of several reasons coalition forces dominated the air war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] American-made color photocopiers were used to produce some of Iraq's battle plans.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Some of the copiers contained concealed high-tech transmitters that revealed their positions to American electronic warfare aircraft, leading to more precise bombings.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The role of Iraq's Scud missiles featured prominently in the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Scud is a tactical ballistic missile that the Soviet Union developed and deployed among the forward deployed Soviet Army divisions in East Germany.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Scud missiles utilize inertial guidance which operates for the duration that the engines operate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Iraq used Scud missiles, launching them into both Saudi Arabia and Israel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Some missiles caused extensive casualties, while others caused little damage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The US Patriot missile was used in combat for the first time.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The US military claimed a high effectiveness against Scuds at the time, but later analysis gives figures as low as 9%, with 45% of the 158 Patriot launches being against debris or false targets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Dutch Ministry of Defense, which also sent Patriot missiles to protect civilians in Israel and Turkey, later disputed the higher claim.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Further, there is at least one incident of a software error causing a Patriot missile's failure to engage an incoming Scud, resulting in deaths.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Both the US Army and the missile manufacturers maintained the Patriot delivered a "miracle performance" in the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The Gulf War has been the subject of several video games including *Conflict: Desert Storm*, *Conflict: Desert Storm II*, *Gulf War: Operation Desert Hammer*, and *Call of Duty: Black Ops 6* (Which was banned in Kuwait).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] There have also been numerous depictions in film including *Jarhead* (2005), which is based on US Marine Anthony Swofford's 2003 memoir of the same name.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] The 2016 Bollywood movie *Airlift* is based on the 1990 airlift of Indians from Kuwait, the evacuation of Indian citizens stranded in Kuwait during the Gulf War.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1991-gulf-war-p03] Gil Scott-Heron's song 'Work for Peace' from the album 'Spirits' was a response to the war.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Central Television became Ostankino Television, and the First Program of Central Television became known as Channel 1 Ostankino.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company "Ostankino" was entrusted with the function of covering political, cultural and economic life in the CIS member states.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Yegor Yakovlev became the Chairman of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the initial stage, there were few changes compared to the last years of the existence of the Soviet Central Television.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The news program was Novosti, and the information and analytical program was Itogi with Yevgeny Kiselyov.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The channel's logo was a stylized image of a unit enclosed in a square.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Since 1992, the socio-political talk show "Tema" with Vladislav Listyev, the analytical talk show "Red Square" with Alexander Lyubimov and the program "Politburo", hosted by Alexander Politkovsky began to be broadcast.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The producer of these programs was the television company VID.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The main problem of the activities of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino was the "spread" of advertising among thematic studios, which began during the existence of the USSR State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1990–1991, three thematic studios received the status of legal entities, including the Experiment studio, which was the main customer for the production of television programs at JSC VID Television Company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the beginning of 1992, instead of almost all other thematic main editorial offices of Central Television, thematic studios of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino were created; for example, ITA had its own advertising department.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Some of the studios paid private television organizations for the programs produced to their order with their advertising time.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The Main Advertising and Commercial Directorate itself was created only in May 1993; the Ostankino Advertising Agency, which operated before that, only placed advertising between programs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In the summer of 1992, Eduard Sagalaev created MNVK, which took over the evening of 6 TVK in Moscow (from 1993 to 1994, economic and educational programs of the Severnaya Korona television company were broadcast on Channel 6 in the morning and afternoon).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Instead of Eduard Sagalaev, Igor Malashenko, who had previously been its political director, became the general director of the television and radio company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In the fall of 1992, Russian businessmen founded the OITV company in Israel, which since the fall of 1993 has been retransmitting the signal of one of the belt versions of 1st channel Ostankino abroad.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In particular, such a version of the channel was broadcast in Israel itself, in early February 1994 in Transnistria, for some time in Ukraine, and from the beginning of 1994 in some cities in the European part of Russia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Israeli Russian- and English-language advertising was broadcast on Ostankino International Television, sometimes blocking the broadcasts.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The exact fate of OITV is unknown: presumably, it stopped broadcasting after the launch of ORT, in April–May 1995.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 4, 1992, the broadcast of George Lucas's film Star Wars was removed from the air with the wording "pirated film purchased for showing without film and video rights".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] This was the first removal from the air on domestic television.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The space saga was shown on Channel One only 13 years later, in 2005, with stereo sound.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On November 24, 1992, Yegor Yakovlev was dismissed due to the showing of a film about the war between Ingushetia and North Ossetia–Alania.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On January 11, 1993, Vyacheslav Bragin was appointed Chairman of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company "Ostankino".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Due to disagreements over the methods of managing the television and radio company, Igor Malashenko left the post of General Director, and his place was taken by Oleg Slabynko.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Under the leadership of Bragin and Slabynko, the channel began to work more often in the interests of Boris Yeltsin, while state censorship began to strengthen.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] ITA editor-in-chief Oleg Dobrodeev and host of the Itogi program Yevgeny Kiselyov considered it impossible to work under the current conditions and, together with Igor Malashenko and businessman Vladimir Gusinsky, founded the NTV television company, which took over production of the Itogi program.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] From the fall of 1993 to the spring of 1994, Ostankino experienced a large outflow of ITA journalists and employees of some other departments, who transferred to the staff of NTV Television Company LLC.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, many employees of the television and radio company began to leave for the new channel TV-6, created by the former head of the television and radio company Eduard Sagalaev.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] After this, only Channel Five and RTR remained on the air, which broadcast Vesti every half hour, and also retransmitted a live CNN broadcast.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 4 at 6:30 the broadcast was resumed, and footage of the siege was shown on Teleutra, as well as a live broadcast of the storming of the White House.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] After these events, Vyacheslav Bragin demanded that security be strengthened at the buildings of the television and radio company's editorial offices and studios.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On December 16, 1993, Vyacheslav Bragin resigned from the post of chairman of the Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] This position was initially offered to Vladimir Mukusev, but due to his conflict with the television company's staff, this candidacy was withdrawn.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] This position was also offered to Yevgeny Kiselyov, but he refused.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Alexander Yakovlev was appointed chairman, and Oleg Tochilin was appointed editor-in-chief of the Information Television Agency.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] By February 1994, Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company and All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company had accumulated debt to state-owned communications enterprises: as of January 1, 1996, they amounted to 412 billion rubles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The employees of Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company saw the solution in the creation of trading houses controlled by the television and radio company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Since October 1992, the commercial Russian-language television channel Orsent TV has been broadcasting on the frequencies of the Ostankino 1st Channel in Estonia at night, after the channel's broadcasts have ended.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1993–1994, this channel's broadcasts were conducted from 5 to 6 p.m., thus, the broadcasts of Ostankino in Estonia at this time were overlapped by Orsent TV programs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] According to the concluded agreement, the channel could broadcast on the air of LitPollinter TV for only a few hours.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On February 6, 1995, the LitPollinter TV channel stopped broadcasting due to financial problems, and the 1st Ostankino Channel in Lithuania began broadcasting in pure form again (however, on April 1 it was replaced by ORT, and on May 5 ORT transferred the frequency to the LNK channel).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Initially, the channel was of an informational and artistic nature.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The weekday program consisted of news, popular science, cultural and educational, documentary programs, one-part television films and mini-series, distributed under the headings "Homebody", "Third Age" and "Children's Hour".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] However, due to the reduction in expenses on state television, which occurred in an earlier period, the channel reduced the number of programs prepared and television films produced.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Over time, they were replaced by entertainment programs, which were produced mainly by private television organizations.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Some airtime was given over to showing domestic and foreign films, combined into several sections (for example, In the Detective Club on Fridays from September 4, 1992).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] As a result of all this, the volume of production of domestic television films fell sharply, and the production capacities of the Studio Ekran and the Television Technical Center began to stand idle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In late 1992 and early 1993, the television game show for teenagers, Star Hour and the children's television game show, Call of the Jungles, as well as the program, When Everyone is Home also appeared.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On September 19, 1993, the program "Itogi" was broadcast for the last time.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Then, from October 10, 1993, it began to be broadcast on Channel 5, and from January 23, 1994 - on Channel 4, part of whose airtime was taken up by the NTV television company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Instead of the program "Itogi", information and analytical programs "Voskresenye" with Sergei Alekseev and "Novosti Plus" with Sergey Medvedev began to be broadcast.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1994, a new wave of expansion of the number of programs produced by private television organizations on the air occurred.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Since May 1994, the topical interview show "Rush Hour" has been aired on weekdays, hosted by Vladislav Listyev; the producer of this program was the television company "VID", and the program was aired daily in prime time, at 19:10.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The host of the program Tema was Lidiya Ivanova.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The program "Red Square" also resumed its broadcast under the old name "Vzglyad", hosted by Alexander Lyubimov, and six months before that, the program "Politburo" resumed its broadcast.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Cultural and educational programs began to be aired in prime time - So That They Remember" and "Silver Ball".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Since the end of 1993, talk shows produced by the ATV television company began to be broadcast on Mondays: We and If, hosted by Vladimir Pozner, and A Man and a Woman with Kira Proshutinskaya.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In certain periods, private television organizations produced up to 70% of television programs, excluding news, films and archival recordings.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Since July 4, 1994, due to the cutback in funding for Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company and the need to reduce the broadcasting time of 1st channel Ostankino to 12 hours, a technical break was added to the channel's weekday program from 11:20 to 16:00.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] GMS took on the compilation of a program digest, on the basis of which Igor Krutoy's firm ARS, commissioned by the television company, produced the television program Compass GMS.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Advertising placement was subordinated to GMS's own advertising agency.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The GMS weekday program usually consisted of 8-minute news releases every hour, two repeat showings of feature films (since October 1994 - one film) and some kind of cultural, educational or entertainment program.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] By the beginning of September, it became available in twelve more cities in Russia, while in the remaining cities there was a break in broadcasting during the daytime.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, in some neighbouring countries, the channel did not broadcast at all due to the peculiarities of time zones.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] A new broadcasting schedule was adopted on October 3, 1994: from now on, news releases were broadcast at the 52nd minute of each hour, overlapping programs that were broadcast at that time, the timing of each news release was 8 minutes (such a broadcasting schedule initially existed on GMS).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The Vremya programs (as the 21:00 news broadcasts were again called in December 1994) were not affected by these changes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the end of 1994, RGTRK Ostankino demanded that non-state television companies "share" some of their prime time, which meant closing some of the programs of non-state television companies.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Then the television companies "VID", "ATV", "REN-TV" and "Klass!" created the Association of Independent Television Producers, which came up with the initiative to create Public Russian Television (ORT), the majority of whose shares would belong to various business representatives.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Broadcasting on Channel 1 Ostankino was supposed to go to it.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] This joint-stock company was given the right to place advertising on the channel.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] RGTRK Ostankino did not receive any dividends for 1994 from the holding, and the holding's debt to the television and radio company as of July 1, 1995 amounted to 19.0 billion rubles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] According to the initial proposal, 15% each belonged to the private television organizations Television Company VID, ATV, Television Company REN-TV, and RTV-Press, 20% to the bankers, and 20% to the state.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] This joint-stock company was founded at its all-Russian constituent meeting of shareholders on January 24, 1995.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Vladislav Listyev was appointed General Director of ORT, Badri Patarkatsishvili and Kirill Ignatyev were appointed his first deputies, and the chairman of the board of directors of ORT was the chairman of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino, Alexander Yakovlev.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] ORT broadcasting was originally planned to begin on February 1, 1995.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] A decision was also made to introduce a moratorium on advertising from March 1.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] But on the evening of that very day, Listyev was killed in the entrance to his own home three hours after the Rush Hour program.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On March 20, Sergei Blagovolin became General Director of ORT.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Its director was Midkhat Shilov, who had previously been responsible for literary and artistic editing.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On April 1, 1995, the channel's frequencies were transferred to ORT.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] News broadcasts, as before 1994, began to be broadcast on the usual schedule, at 9:00, 12:00, 15:00, 18:00 and after midnight with a duration of 20 minutes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The announcer service was abolished (now announcers did not work on camera).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Daytime breaks were also excluded from the broadcasting grid (retained in some subjects of the Russian Federation), while JSC "GMS" did not disappear from the air - it continued to broadcast under the ORT logo.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] For a short time, the television and radio company became the producer of a number of programs, series and cycles.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Among them were: the next season of the TV series "The Little Things of Life", meetings with Alexander Solzhenitsyn, "Play, My Favorite Accordion!", etc.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In addition, its area of responsibility included organizing sports broadcasts and providing Soviet feature films and animated films for reruns.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The information television agency continued to produce news for the ORT television channel, the Vremya program, the morning channel Teleutro, and the final analytical television magazine "Sunday".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] The main socio-political talk show of ORT was the program One on One (TV program), hosted by Alexander Lyubimov, and the hosts of the program "Rush Hour" were Sergei Shatunov and Dmitry Kiselev [228].
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] Many programs that survived from the times of either the RGTRK "Ostankino" or the Central Television of the USSR were closed already during the active work of ORT.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 6, 1995, the decree of the president of Russia on the liquidation of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino was published, after which on October 12 it was finally liquidated by a decree of the Government of Russia.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] In March 1996, ITA was liquidated, and the staff involved in providing Ostankino television coverage was laid off, fired, or integrated into the staff of ORT or other channels.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, some former ITA employees, such as Oleg Tochilin and Yulia Rakcheeva, transferred to the NTV television company.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Australia on 24 November 2007.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] All 150 seats in the House of Representatives and 40 of the seats in the 76-member Senate were up for election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The election featured a 39-day campaign, with 13.6 million Australians enrolled to vote.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The centre-left Australian Labor Party opposition, led by Kevin Rudd and deputy leader Julia Gillard, defeated the incumbent centre-right Coalition government, led by Liberal Party leader and Prime Minister, John Howard, and Nationals leader and Deputy Prime Minister, Mark Vaile, by a landslide.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The election marked the end of the 11-year-long Howard-led Liberal–National Coalition government that had been in power since the 1996 election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard lost his own seat, becoming the first sitting Australian Prime Minister to lose his seat in nearly 80 years.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This election also marked the start of the six-year Rudd–Gillard Labor government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Future Prime Minister Scott Morrison, future opposition leader Bill Shorten, and future Deputy Prime Minister Richard Marles entered parliament at this election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This would be the last time the Labor Party would win a majority at the federal level until 2022.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This remains the most recent election in which both major parties won over 40% of first preference votes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] It would also be the last time the Labor Party was ahead of the Liberal–National Coalition in first preference vote until 2025.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd became the third Labor leader after World War II to lead the party to victory from opposition, after Gough Whitlam in 1972, Bob Hawke in 1983, and before most recently Anthony Albanese in 2022.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Although the Coalition was defeated, the results in Western Australia bucked the national trend.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] While there was a swing against the Liberal Party and to the Labor Party, which allowed Labor to gain the seat of Hasluck from the Liberals, the Liberals managed to gain the seats of Cowan and Swan from Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Under the provisions of the Constitution, the current House of Representatives may continue for a maximum of three years from the first meeting of the House after the previous federal election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The first meeting of the 41st Parliament after the 2004 election was on 16 November 2004, hence the parliament would have expired on 15 November 2007 had it not been dissolved earlier.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] There must be a minimum of 33 days and a maximum of 68 days between the dissolution of the House of Representatives and the day of the election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Prime Minister Howard opted for a 39-day campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The prime minister of the day chooses the election date and requests the governor-general to dissolve the House and issue the writs for the election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 14 October, John Howard gained the agreement of the governor-general, Major-General Michael Jeffery, to dissolve the House of Representatives and hold a general election for the House and half the Senate on 24 November 2007.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] During the last term of parliament before the 2007 election, the deadline for new voter enrolment was brought forward from seven working days after the issue of the writ to the same day.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] When the election was announced, the writ was not issued the next day, but on the following Wednesday.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This kept the roll open for three days, during which 77,000 enrolment additions were processed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Roy Morgan polling in June 2007 reported WorkChoices was a reason for Labor party support, and a fear of union dominance and support for Coalition economic management policy as the biggest reasons behind the Coalition vote.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Several big business organisations, including the Australian Industry Group, declined a request from the Prime Minister to run advertisements to counter the union-funded campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The share of voters concerned about industrial relations grew from 31 per cent to 53 per cent in the two years to June 2006, with around three-fifths of voters backing Labor's ability to handle the issue over the Liberal Party.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A Newspoll released in June 2006 reported health and Medicare were the most important issue for voters; 83 per cent of respondents rated it "very important".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Other key issues included education (79 per cent), the economy (67 per cent), the environment (60 per cent) and national security (60 per cent).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Taxation and interest rates, key issues in previous campaigns, were rated very important by 54 per cent and 51 per cent respectively.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Immigration, a key issue in 2001, scored 43 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The poll showed that voters considered Labor marginally better-placed to handle health and education, and gave the government strong backing on the economy and national security.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Kevin Rudd promised Labor would introduce a greenhouse gas emission reduction target of 60 per cent by 2050, ratify the Kyoto protocol and introduce a mandatory renewable energy target (MRET) of 20 per cent by 2020.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Howard government reiterated their position of not ratifying the Kyoto protocol, setting "voluntary aspirational emission reduction targets" and introducing a carbon emissions trading scheme by 2012.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor pledged a $4.7 billion fibre-to-the-node broadband network.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] August 2007 saw, for the first time during an election campaign, a 0.25-point interest-rate rise to 6.5 per cent by the Reserve Bank, the sixth rise since the last election in 2004.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor used the news to argue that the Coalition could not be trusted to keep interest rates low, while Costello argued that interest rates would be higher under Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In November 2007 interest rates were raised for the sixth time since the 2004 election, to a 10-year high of 6.75 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Initial off-the-record statements by police officers falsely attributed the murder to gang violence, leading to a press and political storm around so-called African gangs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] During this period, Immigration Minister Kevin Andrews criticised Sudanese Australians on various occasions for "not fitting in" and suggested they were disposed towards "un-Australian" violence.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] As a result of this discourse, the government decided to cut the percentage of refugee visas given to Africans from 70% to 30%.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Queensland Labor Premier, Anna Bligh, described Andrews' criticism of Sudanese as "disturbing".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] She said: "It has been a long time since I have heard such a pure form of racism out of the mouth of any Australian politician." Labor politician Tony Burke branded Andrews' decision as "incompetent".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] However, Andrew's actions were applauded by the former One Nation politician, Pauline Hanson.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Andrews was accused of helping to fuel assaults of Sudanese.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Andrews defended the system of having refugee quotas against the opinion expressed that intakes of refugees should be variated on the basis of global needs ." In October 2007, Howard "admitted breaking a promise to keep interest rates at record lows".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] During the 2004 campaign, Howard was also cited as giving the same promise, personally, on radio.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Inflation figures released on 24 October indicated underlying inflation was higher than expected, which resulted in seven of eight financial companies believing there will be an interest rate rise when the reserve bank met in the middle of November, the first during an election campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd advocated four-year fixed terms for federal parliaments if elected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard supported four-year terms but opposed fixed election dates.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Any change would require approval by referendum.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In mid-October, Howard said that if re-elected, the government would hold a referendum on the inclusion a statement of reconciliation in the preamble of the constitution.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 14 October, Howard announced a 24 November election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Coalition had been trailing Labor in the polls since 2006, and most pundits predicted that Howard would not be re-elected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] ABC Online election analyst Antony Green noted the Coalition's numbers were similar to what Labor had polled before losing power in 1996.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard's theme concentrated on leadership, stating that the nation *"does not need new leadership, it does not need old leadership.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] It needs the right leadership"* He said his government would strive to achieve full employment, which he argued was less likely under Kevin Rudd.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In response, Rudd also concentrated on leadership, outlining his case for "new leadership".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] He argued that the government had 'lost touch' with the electorate, and that the Labor Party was best suited to deal with challenges that lie ahead.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A Galaxy poll showed a Labor 53–47 per cent Coalition two-party-preferred result, with a 2 per cent gap on primaries, and ACNielsen polling reported a 2 per cent swing to the Coalition, reducing Labor's lead to 54–46.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd dropped 5 per cent as preferred prime minister.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A Newspoll sampling 1,700 voters taken over the weekend prior to the leaders' debate reported a swing to Labor, increasing their two-party-preferred lead to 58 per cent, a rise of 2 points.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor's primary vote increased 3 points to 51 per cent, and the Liberals decreased by 2 points to 34 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd extended his lead by 2 points to 50 per cent, with Howard down by 2 points to 37 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On the first full day of the campaign, Howard and Costello announced a 'major restructuring of the income tax system' with tax cuts worth $35 billion over three years and a tax cut "goal" for the next five years.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A few days later, Rudd released his policy which supported the reform measures, however offered education and health tax rebates instead of immediate cuts to the top rate as proposed by the Liberal Party, with a slower progression for the top rate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals slogan, "go for growth" was launched after announcing the largest tax cut in Australian history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Media and political commentators questioned the suitability of the slogan in the context of rising inflation and interest rates.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] During the latter part of the week union influence over the ALP was questioned after the launch of the Liberal party's first campaign ads.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor responded with commercials attacking the Liberals' campaign as 'smears', which was disputed by John Howard.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] One of the Liberal Party election commercials was corrected after it incorrectly said Wayne Swan and Craig Emerson had previously been union officials.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A debate between the Leader of the Opposition and the Prime Minister, under the moderation of the National Press Club, was shown live on ABC TV, the Nine Network, and Sky News Australia at 7.30 pm on 21 October.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd had called for a minimum of three debates between himself and Howard, while Howard, who had been rated poorly by studio audiences at past leadership debates, pressed for a single debate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A total of 2.4 million Australians watched the event, with Nine averaging 1.42 million, the ABC averaging 907,000, and Sky News averaging 62,000.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The last election debate in 2004 was watched by 1.77 million on Nine and the ABC, while in 2001, average audiences on Nine, Seven and the ABC totalled 2.44 million.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] David Speers, Sky News's political editor, moderated the debate which was held in the Great Hall of Parliament House.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The debate audience was 400, with the Coalition and Labor each selecting 200.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Kevin Rudd argued that the Liberal Party was being influenced by the H.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On the same day, Peter Costello admitted when questioned that the 70 per cent figure was in reference to union members rather than union officials.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd said that Howard had "no plan for the future" on tackling climate change.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard said that a Coalition government would establish a climate change fund after 2011, which would be financed by carbon offsets.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Nine Network, which broadcast the debate as an extended edition of *60 Minutes*, used 'the Worm' in its broadcast despite prior objections from the Liberal Party and action from the National Press Club to cease its video feed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] As a result, the Nine Network's feed was cut part way into the broadcast, which Nine then replaced with Sky News's coverage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Nine television network's live audience, via the Worm's average, scored the debate 65 to 29 in Rudd's favour, with 6 per cent remaining undecided.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Nine had a separate group of 80 it said were 'swinging' voters (chosen by McNair Research) in its studio to control 'the Worm'.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Steps were taken to ensure equal numbers so as not to taint the Worm.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At one point, Peter Costello was asked to cease interjecting.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Figures released on the Tuesday, showed a stronger than expected underlying rate of inflation of 3 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Treasurer Peter Costello argued against an increase in interest rates, saying the Reserve Bank should concentrate on the headline consumer price index (CPI) inflation rate which rose of 1.9 per cent for the period.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Controversy arose over the Coalition's climate change policy, with *The Financial Review* citing "government sources" who claimed Turnbull told Cabinet six weeks ago it should sign the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Neither Howard nor Turnbull denied the story.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The story said that "internal critics" are claiming Turnbull is "selfishly positioning himself for a Coalition defeat" and a "possible post-poll leadership battle with Treasurer Peter Costello".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The story led to claims of major splits in Cabinet.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor also suffered from mixed messages.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Kevin Rudd was compelled to clarify Labor policy on climate change after an interview in which Peter Garrett suggested Labor would sign up to the post-Kyoto agreement at 2012 even if carbon-emitting developing countries did not.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd's comments, which he described as having "always been [Labor's] position", saw Labor's policy move closer to Liberal policy, insofar as Labor would ratify the agreement only after persuading all major carbon emitters, developing and developed, to ratify.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Rudd also committed Labor to a target of a 20 per cent reduction in emissions by 2020, a 5-point increase on the Liberal target, assisted by the use of renewable energy, but without the use of coal pollution mitigation, arguing that it would ultimately be a benefit, not a detriment to the economy.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] John Howard said the Coalition would not match Labor's promise of 20 per cent renewable energy target.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard claimed Labor's policy "imposes too many additional costs to industry".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Peter Garrett replied that lack of government action has cost jobs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] ABC Radio reported that Howard had rejected a 2005 recommendation for higher renewable energy targets by his Environment Minister, but Howard declined to confirm or deny the claim.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Coalition announced a promise to open 50 new emergency medical centres on Australia if re-elected.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Adding to the campaign trend of both major parties criticising their opponent for plagiarism and "me-tooism", Labor responded that the government had copied its policy.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Peter Garrett was criticised by the Coalition when radio announcer Steve Price revealed Garrett had said to TV presenter Richard Wilkins that, "once we get in we'll just change it all" in reference to copying Coalition policies.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Garrett said the comment was made during a "short, jocular and casual" conversation and Wilkins supported Garrett's response, saying that it was a "light-hearted throwaway line".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard said his party planned to lift the rate to 3.5 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Commentators pronounced Peter Costello and Wayne Swan's debate on 30 October as ending in a draw.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Costello focused mainly on the government's past record, advocating the need for Australia to build into the future, while Swan said Labor were interested in "investing in people".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard said he believed Costello "creamed" his opponent, while Rudd said Swan did a "fantastic job".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Liberal Tony Abbott and Labor's Nicola Roxon debated health at the National Press Club on ABC television.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Abbott's character and ministerial capacity were questioned by Roxon for his comments about terminally ill asbestos campaigner Bernie Banton and for arriving 35 minutes late to debate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At the end of the debate, Roxon suggested to Abbott that he "could have arrived on time" if he had "really wanted to", to which Abbott replied "bullshit".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Former Liberal campaign strategist Sue Cato said "you just don't run late for things like that".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Abbott apologised to Banton but not to Roxon.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 10 November, the Australian Democrats held their campaign launch in Melbourne under the banner of *Bring Back Balance*, a reference to their central campaign theme of preventing the government from regaining absolute control of the Senate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Reserve Bank of Australia adjusted interest rates upwards by another 0.25 per cent, the sixth rise since the last election, to a 10-year high of 6.75 per cent, and the first time the Bank had been changed rates during an election campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Coalition said that only the current government had the proper experienced team to manage the economy in future, less prosperous years.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Costello argued that the inflationary reasons for the rate rise were "outside the control of a Government".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In response, Labor accused the Coalition of having "hauled up the white flag in the fight against inflation", saying that they had backflipped from their past statements that they could keep interest rates low.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard stated that he was sorry for the negative consequences for and burden on Australian borrowers, but subsequently denied that this constituted an apology for the rate rise itself.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 7 November, Workplace Relations Minister Joe Hockey and Labor's Julia Gillard debated industrial relations including WorkChoices at the National Press Club in Canberra.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Hockey argued that Labor's policy to drop Workchoices was Australia's biggest threat to inflation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 8 November, Environment Minister Malcolm Turnbull and opposition spokesman Peter Garrett debated environment issues at the National Press Club in Canberra.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Garrett criticised the government's record on climate change to which Turnbull responded that Garrett's current claims betray his previous career as a political activist.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Both major parties had their official campaign launches in Brisbane, Queensland; the Liberal Party on Monday 12 November and Labor on Wednesday 14 November.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At their launch, the Coalition pledged a rebate for education costs, including private school fees, of all Australian children, totalling $9.4 billion.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Under the plan, primary school students would have been eligible for $400, while secondary-school students would have been eligible for $800.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Tax cuts worth $1.6 billion over four years were proposed to encourage people to save for first homes, and extra funding of $652 million for child care and $158 million to support carers was promised.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Labor Party promised to spend only a quarter of the $9.4 billion promised by the Coalition, saying it would have a smaller impact on inflation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] It accused the Howard government of being "irresponsible".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In addition to previous education funding announcements, Rudd promised Labor would provide an additional 65,000 apprenticeships, migrate all schools to new high speed broadband, and provide all year 9–12 students with access to their own computer.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A doubling of the number of undergraduate and postgraduate scholarships available at a tertiary level was announced, and the party re-iterating its view on climate change and WorkChoices.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Labor Party released footage on Thursday 15 November to Lateline, showing Tony Abbott addressing a room of people, stating "I accept that certain protections, in inverted commas, are not what they were" in reference to WorkChoices legislation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Referring to award structures, Abbott said in the same footage: "I accept that that has largely gone.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] I accept that." When questioned, Abbott said he stood by the comments that WorkChoices means "certain protections" are not what they used to be, but denied conceding workers had lost protections.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] He said the video released by Labor was a *"cut-and-paste job"*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Newspoll stated Labor's two-party-preferred level was down one point to 54 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Former Liberal Party campaign director Lynton Crosby said that the Coalition was "closing in on Labor" in the final week and could "still win a tight election" on a campaign of defending marginal seats, declaring a win still possible on 48.5 per cent of the two-party-preferred vote.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 20 November, John Howard defended the government's advertising spending in the months prior to the campaign, paid for with public money.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The advertising, which covered topics including the controversial "Workchoices", cost $360 million over approximately 18 months.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] An article in the 20 November issue of the *Herald Sun* suggested spending could have been up to $500 million, though this took a broader view of what was included in that sum.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard was criticised for not revealing documents written by his department about further changes to industrial relations laws in addition to WorkChoices legislation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In response, the government said the proposals had been cancelled, and that WorkChoices would not be expanded upon.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Seven Network failed in attempt to access the documents under Freedom of Information.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Nationals Senator Barnaby Joyce said that the possibility of his crossing the floor to support Labor's amendments to WorkChoices remained open, and that he would judge all legislation on its merits, for which he was criticised by Nationals leader Mark Vaile.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 21 November, three days before the election, fake pamphlets were distributed in the electorate of Lindsay, which purported to be from an Islamic group.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The group was non-existent and the pamphlets thanked the Labor Party for supporting the Bali bombers and encouraged people to vote Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Those involved included a member of the Liberals' state executive, Jeff Egan; Gary Clark, husband of retiring MP Jackie Kelly; and Greg Chijoff, the husband of Lindsay candidate Karen Chijoff.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Kelly said the incident was a "*Chaser*-style prank." John Howard condemned the statement.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Egan and Greg Chijoff were immediately expelled from the Liberal Party a day before John Howard's address to the Australian Press Club; although, Egan denied any wrongdoing.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] After the election Greg Chijoff, Clark and a third man were fined over the scandal, as the pamphlet were considered electoral material that required an authorisation disclosure statement.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] It also lead to a breakdown in the Chijoff marriage.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Citing a clause of the Constitution that states parliamentarians are not permitted to hold an "office of profit under the crown", government frontbencher Andrew Robb said that up to 13 Labor candidates standing in the election may be ineligible for nomination.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] According to Robb, a "search of public records" indicated that the 13 candidates may have still been employed by government agencies, boards or offices, and that the Liberal Party may consider legal challenges to their election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] According to Labor Senator Penny Wong, all Labor's candidates were eligible to stand, and that the Liberals had obtained the information from outdated websites.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Election night was covered extensively by three of the Australian free-to-air networks, from the National Tally Room: ABC Television, the Nine Network and the Seven Network.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Network Ten and SBS Television included brief updates and news bulletins through the night, but not to the other networks' extent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Sky News offered extensive coverage on Pay TV.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Roy Morgan, Newspoll, ACNeilsen and Galaxy timegraph polling showed Labor leading the Coalition in opinion polling from mid-2006 onward.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On several key questions, Labor increased its lead after Rudd assumed the Labor leadership from Kim Beazley, at which point Rudd also assumed the lead as preferred prime minister.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] While Labor was ahead in opinion polling, Howard had led Beazley on this question by a wide margin.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] According to Australian political analyst Adam Carr, WorkChoices was one of five key reasons for "...a change of heart by the decisive sectors of the electorate".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The new industrial relations program, Carr said, angered the "Howard battlers" – the traditional Labor voters who had supported Howard for most of the last 11 years – because they saw it as a direct attack on their livelihood.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] ACNielsen polling in March 2007 had Rudd's personal approval rating at 67 per cent, which made him the most popular opposition leader in the poll's 35-year history, with Newspoll (News Limited) 2PP polling the highest in its history at 61%.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The largest 2PP election result for the ALP in its history was at the 1943 election on an estimate of 58.2 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] By the time the writs were issued, the Coalition was well behind Labor in opinion polling, which election analyst Antony Green believed to show Labor winning government "in a canter".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] According to Green, this was a nearly exact reversal of the run-up to the 1996 election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Coalition was running ahead of Labor in two-party opinion polling for much of 1995 and 1996, however the mantle of preferred prime minister regularly switched between Howard and Paul Keating.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Polling consistently showed that the economy and national security were the Coalition's strong areas.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] In August 2007 an Ipsos poll showed 39 per cent of voters thought Labor was a better economic manager, compared to 36 per cent for the Coalition, with 25 per cent undecided.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The morning of the election announcement, a special Sun-Herald Taverner survey of 979 people across New South Wales and Victoria had been released, indicating a Labor 2PP of 59 per cent, with the 18- to 29-year-old category voting at 72 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The fortnightly Newspoll was released the day after the election was called, showing the 2PP remaining steady at Labor 56–44 Liberal.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard increased his Preferred PM rating up one per cent to 39 per cent, while Rudd increased his rating up one per cent to 48 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On the day after the election was called, Centrebet had odds of 1.47 on Labor, with 2.70 on the Coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Halfway through the campaign, with no overall change in the polls, saw Centrebet odds for Labor shorten to 1.29, with the Liberals on 3.60.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Centrebet odds two days out from the election were at 1.22 for Labor, with 4.35 for the Coalition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Newspoll a week out from the election of 3,600 voters in 18 of the Coalition's most marginal seats revealed an ALP 54–46 Coalition 2PP, a swing to Labor of 6–9 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] A uniform swing would see 18–25 seats fall to Labor, The Australian said.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Former Labor number-cruncher Graham Richardson, who news.com.au (News Limited) claims to have correctly picked the winner of every election for the past three decades, tipped Kevin Rudd and Labor to win with a 6–7 per cent two-party-preferred, 20-seat swing.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The election-eve Newspoll and Galaxy poll reported the ALP on a 2PP of 52 per cent, Roy Morgan on 53.5 per cent, with ACNielsen on 57 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Seven News reported that TAB had updated their odds for the election, with Labor having safe odds of $1.20 and the Coalition an outside chance on $4.60.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Sky News-Channel 7-Auspoll exit polls on election day of 2,787 voters in the 31 most marginal seats suggested a 53 per cent two-party preferred figure to Labor, 53 per cent to Labor in Bennelong, and 58 per cent to Labor in Eden-Monaro.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At 8.00 pm, the first personality to call the election was former Labor Prime Minister Bob Hawke on Sky News.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At 10.29 pm AEST, approximately two hours after the last polls in Western Australia closed, Liberal deputy leader Peter Costello conceded that the Coalition had lost government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At 10.36 pm, John Howard delivered a speech at the Sofitel Sydney Wentworth to concede defeat.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] At 11.05 pm, Kevin Rudd delivered his victory speech.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor won 83 of the 150 seats in the incoming House of Representatives.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This represented a 23-seat swing to Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals won 55 while the Nationals won 10, with two seats retained by Independents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor finished with a 52.70 per cent two-party-preferred vote, a 5.44-point swing from 2004.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On preferences, 79.7 per cent of Green votes flowed to Labor, 60.3 per cent of Family First votes flowed to the Coalition, with 62.5 per cent of Democrat votes flowing to Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The swing was the largest since 1983, when full preference counting was introduced to create an exact two-party figure, and the largest swing to occur in the absence of a recession, political or military crisis.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Western Australia went against the national trend, with the Liberals suffering only a 2.14-point swing against them – lower than all except Tasmania and the ACT – but yet gaining one net seat.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] As of 2024, The 2007 election was the last time the National party received over 5% of the vote for the House of Representatives.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Labor and the Coalition won 18 seats each in the half-Senate election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Greens won three seats, with Independent Nick Xenophon being elected on primary votes alone.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This took the 76-member Senate total to 37 Coalition, 32 Labor, 5 Green, 1 Family First, and 1 Independent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] With a majority being 39 senators, when the new Senate met after 1 July 2008, the balance of power was shared between Xenophon, Family First's Steve Fielding and the five Greens.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Xenophon, although reported as left-of-centre, indicated plans to work closely with the renegade National, Senator Barnaby Joyce.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] If sufficient Coalition senators voted for government legislation, support from the crossbench was not required.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Xenophon's election was at the expense of a Liberal candidate, without his presence the Coalition would have held enough Senate seats to block legislation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Compared to the previous Senate, the Greens gained one (losing Kerry Nettle in NSW but gaining Sarah Hanson-Young in SA and Scott Ludlam in WA), a new Independent was elected (Xenophon), and Labor gained four seats.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The Coalition lost two, and the Democrats lost all four of their seats.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The informal rate of 2.55 per cent ties with the 1993 election as the lowest informal rate in the Senate since federation.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The introduction of the group voting ticket at the 1984 election saw the number of informal votes drop dramatically.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Prime Minister John Howard lost his own seat of Bennelong, in Northern Sydney, to Labor candidate and former journalist Maxine McKew, becoming the second sitting prime minister, and the third party leader, since Federation to be defeated in his own electorate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Prime Minister Stanley Bruce and National Party leader Charles Blunt lost their seats in 1929 and 1990 respectively.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard had held the seat since 1974, and it had been in Liberal hands ever since its creation in 1949.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] However, successive redistributions, along with demographic change, had made the once safe Liberal seat much friendlier to Labor; much of the area was represented by Labor at the state level.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard's two-party majority was four percent, putting it right on the edge of seats that Labor would likely take in the event it won.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Late on election night, when conceding Labor had won government, Howard also acknowledged the likelihood he had lost Bennelong to McKew, though he and McKew agreed the margin was "very tight".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] He had been ahead by thin margins for most of the night, never leading by more than 0.2 percentage points.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard had been 206 votes ahead of McKew on the first count, and finished 2.8 percentage points behind McKew on the estimated two-party vote.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] McKew declined to claim victory at first, saying that the seat was on "a knife edge," while the Australian Broadcasting Corporation listed Bennelong as a Labor gain on election night, and ABC election analyst Antony Green said there was "no doubt" McKew had won.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] On 29 November, Rudd named McKew as a parliamentary secretary (assistant minister) to be appointed on 3 December, and on 1 December, McKew claimed victory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Although counting was incomplete at the time, with several postal and absentee ballots outstanding, it was expected that Howard would not win enough of the votes to retain his seat.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] McKew finished with a primary vote of 45.33 per cent, and a two-party-preferred vote of 51.40 per cent, a 5.53-point swing from 2004.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Howard lost on the 14th count due to a large flow of Green preferences to McKew.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] This swing was within the redistributed boundaries after the 2004 election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] Three other Howard ministers were defeated – Mal Brough, Gary Nairn and Jim Lloyd.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] The following table indicates seats that changed hands from one party to another at this election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] It compares the election results with the previous margins, taking into account the redistribution in New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p01] As a result, it includes the newly created electorate of Flynn, and the existing Parramatta, which was retained by Labor despite becoming a notional Liberal seat due to boundary changes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The Labor caucus met on Thursday 29 November 2007 to confirm the First Rudd Ministry, which was sworn in on 3 December.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] In a departure from Labor tradition, the ministry was selected by Kevin Rudd as the prime minister, rather than by Caucus.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Given John Howard's personal defeat, the Liberal Party began the process of choosing a new leader.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The morning after the election, Peter Costello, the Deputy Leader of the Liberal Party, and long regarded as Howard's natural successor, stated that he would not run for Liberal leadership.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The day before the ballot, former Health Minister Tony Abbott withdrew from the leadership after initially indicating he would stand.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The leadership ballot was held on Thursday 29 November.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The previous Defence Minister Brendan Nelson and former Environmental Minister Malcolm Turnbull both stood for the leadership.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Former Education Minister Julie Bishop contested the deputy leadership position, as did Andrew Robb and Christopher Pyne.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Brendan Nelson was elected leader by 45 votes to 42, and Julie Bishop was elected deputy leader.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] A Newspoll survey taken after the Liberal leadership change revealed a preferred-prime-minister rating of Rudd 61 per cent to Nelson 14 per cent, with Turnbull twice as popular as Nelson.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Newspoll's subsequent polling saw new Newspoll records set, at 70 per cent for the best rating for preferred prime minister, to 9 per cent for the worst rating for preferred prime minister, with the next poll results revealing another record of 73 to 7 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] A new two party preferred record was also set, at 63 to 37 per cent Labor's way.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Post-election, ALP secretary Tim Gartrell commented on pre-election campaign billboard ads featuring a picture of John Howard stating "Working families in Australia have never been better off", which looked like Liberal Party advertisements, were actually paid for by the Labor Party.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Liberal leader Brendan Nelson declared that the Liberal Party had listened and learned from the Australian public and declared WorkChoices "dead".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] In 2008, former ministers Peter McGauran, Alexander Downer, and Mark Vaile resigned from parliament, sparking Gippsland, Mayo, and Lyne by-elections.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] The Lyne by-election resulted in independent Rob Oakeshott being elected, reducing the total number of Coalition seats to 64.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Bradfield and Higgins by-elections were held in December 2009.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] In September 2008, Malcolm Turnbull replaced Brendan Nelson in a leadership spill, and Barnaby Joyce replaced CLP Senator and Nationals deputy leader Nigel Scullion as leader of the Nationals in the Senate, and moved the party to the crossbenches.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2007-australian-federal-election-p02] Joyce stated that his party would no longer necessarily vote with their Liberal counterparts in the upper house.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A double dissolution election was held on 2 July 2016 to elect all 226 members of the 45th Parliament of Australia, after an extended eight-week official campaign period.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] It was the first double dissolution election since the 1987 election and the first under a new voting system for the Senate that replaced group voting tickets with optional preferential voting.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In the 150-seat House of Representatives, the one-term incumbent Coalition government was reelected with a reduced 76 seats, marking the first time since 2004 that a government had been reelected with an absolute majority.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor picked up a significant number of previously government-held seats for a total of 69 seats, recovering much of what it had lost in its severe defeat of 2013.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On the crossbench, the Greens, the Nick Xenophon Team, Katter's Australian Party, and independents Wilkie and McGowan won a seat each.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] For the first time since federation, a party managed to form government without winning a plurality of seats in the two most populous states, New South Wales and Victoria.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] One re-count was held by the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) for the Division of Herbert, confirming that Labor won the seat by 37 votes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The final outcome in the 76-seat Senate took over four weeks to complete.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Announced on 4 August, the results revealed a reduced plurality of 30 seats for the Coalition, 26 for Labor, and a record 20 for crossbenchers including 9 Greens, 4 from One Nation and 3 from the Xenophon Team.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Former broadcaster and Justice Party founder Derryn Hinch won a seat, while Jacqui Lambie, Liberal Democrat David Leyonhjelm and Family First's Bob Day retained theirs.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Coalition will require nine additional votes for a Senate majority, an increase of three.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Both major parties agreed to allocate six-year terms to the first six senators elected in each state, while the last six would serve three-year terms.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor and the Coalition each gained a six-year Senator at the expense of Hinch and the Greens, who criticised the major parties for rejecting the "recount" method despite supporting it in two bipartisan senate resolutions in 1998 and 2010.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A number of initially elected senators were declared ineligible a result of the 2017–18 Australian parliamentary eligibility crisis, and replaced after recounts.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Voting is compulsory but subject to constitutional constraints.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The decision as to the type of election and its date is for the Prime Minister, who advises the Governor-General to set the process in motion by dissolving the lower or both houses and issuing writs for election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Section 13 of the constitution requires that in half-Senate elections the election of state senators must take place within one year before the places become vacant.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Since the normal terms of half the senators would have ended on 30 June 2017, the writs for a half-Senate election could not be issued earlier than 1 July 2016, and the earliest possible date for a simultaneous House/half-Senate election would have been 6 August 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] There is no constitutional requirement for simultaneous elections for the Senate and the House of Representatives, and there are precedents for separate elections; however, governments and the electorate have long preferred that elections for the two Houses take place simultaneously.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A House-only election can be called at any time during a parliamentary term.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Whether held simultaneously with a Senate election or separately, an election for the House of Representatives was required to have been held on or before 14 January 2017, which is calculated under provisions of the constitution and the Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918 (CEA).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Section 28 of the Constitution of Australia provides that the term of a House expires three years from the first sitting of the House, unless it is dissolved earlier.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The previous federal election was held on 7 September 2013.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The 44th Parliament of Australia opened on 12 November 2013 and its term would have expired on 11 November 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Writs for an election can be issued up to ten days after a dissolution or expiry of the House.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Up to 27 days can be allowed for nominations, and the actual election can be set for a maximum of 31 days after close of nominations, resulting in the latest possible House of Representatives election date of Saturday, 14 January 2017.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A double dissolution cannot take place within six months before the date of the expiry of the House of Representatives.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] That meant that a double dissolution could not be granted after 11 May 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Allowing for the same stages indicated above, the last possible date for a double dissolution election was 16 July 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 2 November 2015, Prime Minister Turnbull stated: "I would say around September–October [2016] is when you should expect the next election to be." However, in December 2015, ABC News reported that some "senior Liberal MPs" had been seeking an election as early as March 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] An election held at this time would have required a separate half-Senate election to be held in late 2016 or early 2017.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 21 March 2016, Turnbull announced that the parliament would be recalled for both houses to sit on 18 April to consider for a third time the bills to reinstate the Australian Building and Construction Commission (ABCC).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Turnbull also said that if the Senate failed to pass the bill, then there would be a double dissolution of parliament and an election would be held on 2 July.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The delivery of the federal budget was also brought forward from 10 May to 3 May.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 18 April, the Senate once again rejected the bills to reinstate the ABCC.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 8 May Malcolm Turnbull attended Government House to advise the Governor-General to issue the writs for a double dissolution on 9 May.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] This confirmed the date of the election; 2 July 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In the weeks after 8 May, there were 132,000 additions to the electoral roll, and a total of 687,000 enrolment transactions, and it was estimated that 95% of eligible Australians were enrolled for the election, with a participation rate of those under 24 of 86.7%.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] By 18 April 2016 there were four bills that met the requirements of Section 57 of the constitution for a double dissolution.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 19 April the Prime Minister confirmed that, following the 2016 federal budget set for 3 May, he would advise the Governor-General to call a double dissolution election on Saturday 2 July.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Any or all of these four bills could have been cited in his advice.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On Sunday 8 May 2016, Turnbull visited Government House and formally advised Governor-General Sir Peter Cosgrove to dissolve both Houses of Parliament and issue the writs for a double dissolution election to be held on 2 July 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Governor-General accepted the advice and dissolved both houses of the Parliament the following day, 9 May 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 8 May 2016, the office of the Governor-General released documents relating to the calling of the election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The documents set out a timeline of key dates for the election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Coalition won the 2013 federal election with 90 of the 150 seats in the House of Representatives, on a swing of 17 seats or 3.6 points on a two-party basis, defeating the six-year Labor government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor held 55 seats, and crossbenchers held the remaining five.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Abbott government was sworn into office on 18 September 2013.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Kevin Rudd resigned as Labor's leader following the defeat of the party.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Chris Bowen became the interim leader in the approach to a leadership election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Two candidates, Anthony Albanese and Bill Shorten, declared their candidacy; Shorten was declared the winner on 13 October 2013.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] As a result of lost ballot papers, on 18 February 2014 the High Court of Australia, sitting as the Court of Disputed Returns, ordered a new half-Senate election for Western Australia, which was held on 5 April 2014.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Senator John Madigan resigned from the Democratic Labour Party and became an independent Senator in September 2014, citing long-term internal party tensions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 24 November 2014, Tasmanian Senator Jacqui Lambie resigned from the Palmer United Party and on 13 March 2015, Queensland Senator Glenn Lazarus also announced his resignation from the Palmer United Party; both then sat as independents.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 14 September 2015, the incumbent Prime Minister, Tony Abbott, was challenged for the leadership of the Liberal Party and thus the prime ministership by Malcolm Turnbull, the Minister for Communications.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Turnbull won the vote 54–44 and on 15 September was sworn in as prime minister, starting the Turnbull government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 11 February 2016 Warren Truss, the Deputy Prime Minister, announced his decision to retire from politics at the 2016 federal election and immediately stood aside as Leader of the Nationals.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Barnaby Joyce was elected as Leader and was sworn as the Deputy Prime Minister, and Fiona Nash was elected as Deputy Leader of the Nationals.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Truss also resigned from the Turnbull Ministry.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Ian Macfarlane attempted to defect from the Liberal to the National party room with accompanying demands for additional Nationals cabinet representation, and the Mal Brough–James Ashby diary controversy deepened in the last week of the campaign.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Along with the unexpected by-election swing and Turnbull's significantly lessened personal ratings in the concurrent December Newspoll, some News Corp Australia journalists claimed that Turnbull's honeymoon was over.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Nick Xenophon Team (NXT) listed many candidates throughout Australia, with ABC psephologist Antony Green indicating NXT had a "strong chance of winning lower house seats and three or four Senate seats".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Liberal Senator Michael Ronaldson announced on 18 December 2015 that he would leave parliament before the next election, after moving from the outer ministry in the Abbott government to the backbench in the Turnbull government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] He resigned on 28 February 2016, and the casual vacancy was filled by James Paterson on 9 March 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor Senator Joe Bullock announced on 1 March 2016 that he would be resigning from the Senate after the autumn sittings of parliament, citing—among other reasons—his opposition to same-sex marriage being at odds with the Labor Party's platform to bind its members in a supporting vote after 2019.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Bullock tendered his resignation to Senate President Stephen Parry on 13 April 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The casual vacancy was filled by Pat Dodson on 28 April 2016.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Palmer United Party leader Clive Palmer announced on 4 May 2016 that he would not recontest his seat of Fairfax at the election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 23 May he also ruled out running for a Senate seat.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In the lower house seat of Brisbane, both the Liberal-National and Labor candidates were openly gay; a first in Australian federal political history.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In the 44th Parliament, there were three by-elections.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Rudd resigned from Parliament on 22 November 2013, triggering the 2014 Griffith by-election, which was held on 8 February, with Terri Butler retaining the seat for Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 21 July 2015, Liberal Don Randall died, triggering the 2015 Canning by-election, which was held on 19 September.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Andrew Hastie retained the seat for the Liberal Party, having to rely on preferences after suffering a substantial swing to the Labor candidate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Joe Hockey was not retained as Treasurer in the Turnbull Ministry, and announced his resignation from Parliament shortly afterwards, triggering the 2015 North Sydney by-election which was held on 5 December.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The seat was retained for the Liberal Party by Trent Zimmerman.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Zimmerman won with 48.2% of the primary vote after a larger-than-predicted 12.8-point swing against the Turnbull Coalition government.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] This was only the second time in North Sydney since federation that the successful Liberal candidate failed to obtain a majority of the primary vote and had to rely on preferences.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Zimmerman faced a double-digit primary vote swing—more than triple that of the 2015 Canning by-election—despite the absence of a Labor candidate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor has never been successful in the safe Liberal seat.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Liberal two-candidate vote of 60.2% against independent Stephen Ruff compares with the previous election vote of 65.9% against Labor.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The reduction of 5.7 points cannot be considered a "two-party/candidate preferred swing"—when a major party is absent, preference flows to both major parties do not take place, resulting in asymmetric preference flows.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In November 2014 the Australian Electoral Commission announced that a redistribution of electoral boundaries in New South Wales and Western Australia would be undertaken before the next election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A determination of the states' membership entitlements under the Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918 meant that Western Australia's entitlement increased from 15 to 16 seats, and New South Wales' decreased from 48 to 47 seats.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] A redistribution also occurred in the Australian Capital Territory, as seven years had elapsed since the last time the ACT's boundaries were reviewed.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The new seat created in Western Australia was the Division of Burt, named after the Burt family, specifically Sir Archibald Burt, Septimus Burt and Sir Francis Burt and centred on the south-east areas of metropolitan Perth.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In October 2015, the AEC also announced plans to abolish the seat of Hunter.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Electors in the north of Hunter would have joined New England, while the roughly 40% remainder would have become part of Paterson, where the Liberal margin would have been reduced from a fairly safe 9.8 points to an extremely marginal 0.5 point as a result.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Hunter was first contested at the inaugural 1901 federal election; the AEC's naming guidelines require it to make "every effort" to preserve the names of the original federal divisions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Commission proposed renaming Charlton to Hunter, and in honour of deceased Prime Minister Gough Whitlam.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The final proposal, however, saw Charlton abolished, with Hunter moving slightly eastward to take in much of Charlton's territory.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Additionally, Paterson was made more compact and pushed well to the south, taking in some heavily Labor territory that had previously been in Hunter and Newcastle.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] This had the effect of erasing the Liberals' majority in Paterson; Labor now had a notional majority of 0.5 per cent.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The Division of Fraser in the ACT was renamed Division of Fenner, to honour the late scientist Frank Fenner.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The AEC announced that the name Fraser would be used for a future division in Victoria, named in honour of Malcolm Fraser, a former Prime Minister.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Following the previous election, the Abbott government announced it would investigate changing the electoral system for the Senate.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On 22 February 2016, the Turnbull government announced several proposed changes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In the Senate, the changes had the support of the Liberal/National Coalition, the Australian Greens, and Nick Xenophon.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The legislation passed both houses of the Parliament of Australia on 18 March 2016 after the Senate sat all night debating the bill.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The changes abolished group voting tickets (GVTs) and introduced *optional* preferential voting, along with party logos on the ballot paper.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The ballot paper continues to have a box for each party above a heavy line, with each party's candidates in a column below that party's box below the solid line.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Previously, a voter could either mark a single box *above the line*, which triggered the party's group voting ticket (a pre-assigned sequence of preferences), or place a number in every box *below the line* to assign their own preferences.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] As a result of the changes, voters may assign their preferences for parties above the line (numbering as many boxes as they wish), or individual candidates below the line, and are not required to fill all of the boxes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Both above and below the line voting are now optional preferential voting.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] For above the line, voters will be instructed to write at least their first six preferences; however, a "savings provision" will still count the ballot if less than six were given.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] As a result, fewer votes are expected to be classed as informal; however, more ballots will "exhaust" as a result (i.e. some votes are not counted towards electing any candidate).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] For below the line, voters will be required to number at least their first 12 preferences.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Voters will be free to continue numbering as many preferences as they like beyond the minimum number specified.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Another savings provision will allow ballot papers with at least 6 below the line preferences to be formal, catering for people who confuse the above and below the line instructions.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Antony Green, a psephologist for the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, wrote several publications on various aspects of the proposed Senate changes.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] As with every double dissolution election the entire Senate is re-elected (12 seats per state rather than the usual half Senate election of six seats per state).
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Consequently, the number of votes required to earn a seat (the "quota") is halved.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Due to the abolition of GVTs, it is no longer possible to create "calculators" that assess, with reasonable accuracy, the eventual senate election outcome.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] In its pre-election editorial endorsements, the press overwhelmingly backed the Coalition over Labor—only the Sunday edition of the Melbourne *Age* endorsed the Labor Opposition.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Among the Sunday papers, Turnbull was preferred by Sydney's *Sun-Herald* and *Sunday Telegraph*, Melbourne's *Sunday Herald Sun*, the *Sunday Mail* in Brisbane, the *Sunday Times* in Perth and the *Sunday Mail* in Adelaide.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor won the endorsement of only the *Sunday Age* in Melbourne.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The *Sunday Tasmanian* and *Sunday Territorian* did not publish endorsements prior to this election.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Labor's close ties to the union movement were of concern to many papers, even to the supportive *Sunday Age*, which described the issue as "vexed" and unresolved.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Others went further, fearful that Shorten would not "free Labor from the union shackles that too often oppose sensible reforms," in the words of the *Sun-Herald*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] "Mr Shorten still remains more union boss than potential prime minister," concluded the *Sunday Telegraph*.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] On the economy, there was general concern about the sustainability of Labor's approach to public spending.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The need for political stability was emphasised by the Perth *Sunday Times* and Adelaide *Sunday Mail*: at that time both states faced an uncertain future due to recent downturns in mining, steelmaking and shipbuilding.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The expectation that any Labor government would govern in minority gave the *Mail* pause.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Australia, it wrote, "needs stability ... this country has suffered enough through balance-of-power ... politicians".
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] The metropolitan dailies backed the Coalition without exception.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] Turnbull's personal qualities and platform appealed more to the editors than his short record in office.
[src:australian-broadcasting-corporation/2016-australian-election-p01] *The Age* spoke for many in concluding that "Mr Turnbull deserves the chance to deliver".
